[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Our First Move"]
[Result "*"]

{ 1. e4 has been the most popular move for essentially the entire history of chess!   It's not hard to understand why it's such a common choice. White occupies the center and allows the queen and bishop to develop quickly. If Black allows White another easy move then he or she will play d2-d4 next and fully conquer the center of the board.   That's why I recommend that you fight back for the center right away with 1....e5! }
1. e4 e5
{ A great move by Black!   This course will teach you how to play 1...e5 with confidence. You're going to be able to stop White's plans and develop with a consistent developing scheme in nearly every game. This chapter will give an introduction to the key ideas of 1. e4 e5, also known as the open games.  Let's jump right in. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Our Basic Setup"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
{ Before we get into the details of each variation, let's take a look at our preferred developing plan in most openings.   Already, after the first move it's pretty clear where most of our pieces want to go!   2.d4  This let's us demonstrate one of the points of 1...e5. We can just capture the pawn.  2...exd4  White will need to lose time recapturing on d4. Your opponent doesn't get an opportunity to take over the center. }
2... Nc6 { Black defends e5 and brings the knight to its best square. } 3. Bc4
{ For the moment, we're not focusing too much on White's moves. } 3... Bc5
{ This is generally the best square for our kingside bishop.   Again, we are locking down the d4-square so White won't be able to play d2-d4 and dominate the middle of the board. From c5, our bishop also targets the vulnerable f2-pawn, which will be the target of many tactics. }
4. O-O Nf6
{ The g8-knight will typically develop to f6. This move helps us get ready to castle kingside and attacks the e4-pawn. }
5. d3 d6
{ With a knight on f6 and the rook defending f7 as soon as we castle, Black should have no early problems with king safety. Our next couple of moves are likely to be ...O-O and then we can develop the c8-bishop to e6 or g4 to complete our development.   Even before you worry about learning the variations in this course, please remember the setup we have so far. In most of your games, if you focus on bringing the knights to c6 and f6, the bishop to c5 and get your king to safety, you will get great positions! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "A Successful Attack in the Four Knights Game"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game demonstrates one of our preferred lines in the Four Knights Game, but for the moment we're going to focus on a tactical idea that can crop up in any 1. e4 e5 opening, the vulnerable pawns on f2 and f7.   In this game Black has a chance to take full advantage of White's weak pawn. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6
{ There's no need to learn these specific moves yet, but please notice that Black will develop according to the plan we've already seen. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ Another great square for a knight. The game won't stay symmetrical for long. }
4. d4 exd4
{ We're usually not going to let White keep two pawns in the center. } 5. Nxd4
Bc5
{ Both sides develop toward the center and Black's bishop already starts to think about winning material on the g1-a7 diagonal. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Black recaptures toward the center and supports the d7-d5 advance. } 7. Bd3
O-O
{ Black secures the king and gets ready to fight for the center with ...d7-d5 and ...Rf8-e8. }
8. O-O d5 9. e5
{ This natural-looking move is a mistake. White would be better off exchanging pawns on d5. }
9... Ng4
{ Black attacks the e5-pawn, but also eyes the vulnerable pawns on f2 and h2. White tries to avoid any immediate material losses and that's what leads to disaster. }
10. Na4
{ This counter-attack loses quickly.   10.Bf4  This is relatively best, but White is still in trouble.  10...f6  Black aims to open the f-file and continue the attack.  11.exf6   11.e6  Just giving away the pawn is probably the strongest option for White, but Black can capture the pawn with a great position.  Qxf6  Black attacks the bishop and lines up the rook and queen against the f2-pawn.  12.Bg3  Nxf2  Black wins a key pawn and should win the game. }
10... Qh4
{ Black aims for checkmate on h2, while attacking f2 as well. This simple dark-square fork is a huge problem for White. }
11. Bf4 Bxf2+ { Black wins this pawn first and then sets up checkmate. } 12.
Kh1 Nxh2 { White can't safely capture the knight. } 13. Bxh7+
{ This only slows things down.   13.Bxh2  Bg3  Black checkmates on h2 next move! }
13... Qxh7 14. Rxf2 { White wins a bishop but loses the king. } 14... Nf3+ 15.
Bh2 Qxh2#
{ A nice attacking game by Black. You're not going to win most games this easily, but look for a way to attack f2 and h2.   If you focus on attacking those vulnerable spots and keeping your king defended, you'll win a lot of games. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "More Tactics on f2 and f7"]
[Result "*"]

{ Our second common tactic is the pin that bishops can put on the kingside knights. We can pin the f3-knight and White might pin our knight on f6.   Typically, this pin isn't too big a deal, but if you're able to attack the pinned knight with another piece, it offers a great opportunity to rip open the opposing kingside.   Let's see how it might work. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
{ Before we get into the details of each variation, let's take a look at our preferred developing plan in most openings.   Already, after the first move it's pretty clear where most of our pieces want to go!   2.d4  This let's us demonstrate one of the points of 1...e5. We can just capture the pawn.  2...exd4  White will need to lose time recapturing on d4. Your opponent doesn't get an opportunity to take over the center. }
2... Nc6 { Black defends e5 and brings the knight to its best square. } 3. Bc4
Bc5
{ We begin to target the f2-pawn. This is the Italian Game, which we will learn more about later in the course. }
4. Nc3 Nf6 5. d3 d6
{ Both sides have developed logically. So far everything is the same for each of them, but the fireworks are about to begin. }
6. O-O Bg4 { Black pins the f3-knight and White already must be very careful. }
7. Bg5
{ White pins the black knight, but Black isn't castled yet, so the pin isn't too dangerous. }
7... Nd4
{ When Black captures on f3, White will need to recapture with the g2-pawn, exposing the white king. }
8. Be3 { White tries to admit the mistake, but it's too late to fix it. } 8...
Nxf3+ { Black rips open the white kingside. } 9. gxf3 Bh3
{ Black attacks the f1-rook and aims for a quick mate. Black just needs to find a way to get the queen to g2. }
10. Re1 Nh5 { Making room for the queen to reach the kingside. } 11. Ne2
{ 11.Kh1!  White's best try is hide the king in the corner and control the g-file with the rook. Black still has the safer king and a good position. }
11... Bxe3
{ Black removes the defender of the g5-square and White's position quickly falls apart. }
12. fxe3 Qg5+ { The queen enters the fray and the game is nearly over. } 13.
Ng3 Nxg3 { Clearing the g-file. } 14. hxg3 Qxg3+ { And there's no escape. } 15.
Kh1 Qg2#
{ White never had a chance in this game after Black was able to pin the f3-knight and break open the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
