[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "The Fork Trick"]
[Result "*"]

{ The next tactical trick is very common, but isn't quite as decisive as some of the other ideas we've looked at. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
{ Before we get into the details of each variation, let's take a look at our preferred developing plan in most openings.   Already, after the first move it's pretty clear where most of our pieces want to go!   2.d4  This let's us demonstrate one of the points of 1...e5. We can just capture the pawn.  2...exd4  White will need to lose time recapturing on d4. Your opponent doesn't get an opportunity to take over the center. }
2... Nc6 { Black defends e5 and brings the knight to its best square. } 3. Nc3
Nf6
{ Another great square for a knight. The game won't stay symmetrical for long. }
4. Bc4 { Now the position of the White bishop on c4 gives Black a great move. }
4... Nxe4
{ This is called a fork trick. Black sacrifices a knight, but soon wins it back with a great position. }
5. Nxe4
{ White wins a knight, but won't be able to keep it.   5.Bxf7+?  This way of sacrificing material back gives Black a great game.  5...Kxf7  Black just captures the bishop.  6.Nxe4  White wins back the piece, but Black is already much better.  6...d5  Black has a huge center and the king on f7 is just a temporary inconvenience. }
5... d5 { Black forks the white knight and bishop, winning back the piece. } 6.
Bxd5 Qxd5
{ Black wins back the piece and is left with the only pawn in the center. Black already has a great position. Although, Black played the fork trick in this example, we'll want to watch out for White capturing our e-pawn, aiming fo a fork trick as well. }
