[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Italian Game"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's take a quick looks at the most common variations that you'll get after 1...e5 before we dive into the details in our later chapters. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
{ Before we get into the details of each variation, let's take a look at our preferred developing plan in most openings.   Already, after the first move it's pretty clear where most of our pieces want to go!   2.d4  This let's us demonstrate one of the points of 1...e5. We can just capture the pawn.  2...exd4  White will need to lose time recapturing on d4. Your opponent doesn't get an opportunity to take over the center. }
2... Nc6 { Black defends e5 and brings the knight to its best square. } 3. Bc4
{ White develops and eyes f7. We will develop and aim for the f2-pawn. } 3...
Bc5
{ Black brings the bishop to its best square and gets ready to castle quickly.   3...Nf6  This is playable, but it's dangerous to allow White a way to attack f7.  4.Ng5  Black is OK, but will be forced to sacrifice a pawn. Let's go with a safer option. }
4. d3
{ 4.Ng5?  This no longer works for White.  4...Qxg5  Thanks for the piece. }
4... Nf6
{ Black is able to bring another minor piece to a good square. Now White will typically play Nc3 or c2-c3, which we will cover more in the chapter on the Italian Opening.   For the moment let's just show how easy it is to defend the f7-pawn. }
5. Ng5
{ White's knight is safe here, but your opponent won't get to win the pawn on f7. }
5... O-O
{ Black's king is safe on the kingside and White will probably regret ever playing Ng5. }
6. Nxf7
{ The trade of knight and bishop for rook and pawn is almost always good for Black. }
6... Rxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7
{ Material is about even, but Black is doing well. White has traded off every developed piece. Black already has three pieces on good squares and will soon generate a strong attack. }
