[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Ruy Lopez"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
{ Before we get into the details of each variation, let's take a look at our preferred developing plan in most openings.   Already, after the first move it's pretty clear where most of our pieces want to go!   2.d4  This let's us demonstrate one of the points of 1...e5. We can just capture the pawn.  2...exd4  White will need to lose time recapturing on d4. Your opponent doesn't get an opportunity to take over the center. }
2... Nc6 { Black defends e5 and brings the knight to its best square. } 3. Bb5
{ White hopes to either capture our knight at the right moment, or pin it after we move the d-pawn forward. It's annoying to let the Bxc6 threat remain over our heads, so we will force the bishop back. }
3... a6
{ Black forces the bishop to retreat. Once it's back on a4, we have the option of playing b7-b5 to chase the bishop again. }
4. Ba4
{ 4.Bxc6  We will examine this Exchange in more detail in the Ruy Lopez chapter. The main thing to know is that Black can easily win back the pawn if White captures on e5 right away.  4...dxc6  We want to recapture with the d-pawn to allow the queen and bishop to quickly develop.  5.Nxe5  White won't be able to hold this extra pawn for long.  5...Qd4  Black forks White's knight and the e4-pawn.  6.Nf3  Qxe4+  Black wins back the pawn.  7.Qe2  Qxe2+  White won't be able to castle and Black already has the better game. }
4... Nf6
{ The second knight reaches its favorite square. If White's not careful, we might capture the e4-pawn down the line. }
5. O-O
{ White has many options, but this has been the main move for decades. We will examine the various ways that White could defend the e4-pawn in the Ruy Lopez chapter. }
5... b5
{ We're not interested in capturing on e4 until after we've finished developing. The first priority is making sure that White won't be able to capture on c6 and then e5 when we're not ready for it. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This is the Archangel Variation of the Ruy Lopez, but you don't need to worry about names and multitude of different variations. You just need to remember that your bishop goes to its favorite diagonal. }
7. c3
{ White hopes to place a pawn on d4 and have it well protected by the c-pawn. We want to be ready for that advance, so we're going to protect the d5-pawn a second time. }
7... d6 { Protecting e5 and allowing the c8-bishop to develop. } 8. d4
{ White gets to occupy the center, but our pieces will be targeting it. } 8...
Bb6
{ The bishop is safe here and White will have a hard time taking advantage of having a big pawn center. Black already has three pieces attacking the d4-pawn and one piece attacking the e4-pawn.   Our next couple of moves are likely to be castling and playing Bg4 to pin the f3-knight. If your opponent isn't very careful, you'll be able to win one of the center pawns and go on to win the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Scotch Game"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
{ Before we get into the details of each variation, let's take a look at our preferred developing plan in most openings.   Already, after the first move it's pretty clear where most of our pieces want to go!   2.d4  This let's us demonstrate one of the points of 1...e5. We can just capture the pawn.  2...exd4  White will need to lose time recapturing on d4. Your opponent doesn't get an opportunity to take over the center. }
2... Nc6 { Black defends e5 and brings the knight to its best square. } 3. d4
{ This is the Scotch Game. White aims to take over the center, but we're ready to capture the pawn and develop quickly. }
3... exd4
{ There's no great way to defend the pawn on e5, so we'll capture White's pawn. }
4. Nxd4 Bc5
{ As usual, our minor pieces head to their best squares. White must decide how to save the knight on d4. }
5. Be3
{ This is White's trickiest option.   Now we need to be careful. Notice that White's bishop is lined up on the g1-a7 diagonal with our undefended bishop.   5.Nxc6  If White captures, it's helpful to remember that we don't want to trade queens on d8 and lose our castling rights. Instead, we can make a quick mate threat.  5...Qf6!  Black develops and threatens mate on f2!  6.Qf3  bxc6  The other pawn capture on c6 is good too. Black wins back the piece with a comfortable game.   5.Nb3  White can attack the bishop, but we don't mind too much.  5...Bb6  The bishop finds a safe square on its favorite diagonal.  6.Nc3  Nf6  As usual, our minor pieces all reach good squares and we're ready to castle. }
5... Qf6
{ This is a good move to remember.   Black's queen threatens White's knight and moves out of the way of any tactical tricks. This is one of the rare times that we won't be placing a knight on f6.   5...Nf6??  This let's White play the tactic that Be3 set up.  6.Nxc6  White trades pieces, attacks the black queen and creates a discovery against the c5-bishop. Suddenly Black is losing!  6...bxc6  7.Bxc5  Black loses a piece. That's why it's important to remember to play 5...Qf6. }
6. c3
{ White has to spend time defending the knight so we can continue to develop.   6.Nxc6?  Bxe3  With the queen on f6, we can trade bishops before taking the knight on c6 and Black is doing very well! }
6... Nge7 { With f6 taken, this is the best spot for the g8-knight. } 7. Bc4 b6
{ This is a fun way to develop the bishop.   From b7 it will attack the e4-pawn and the white kingside. We're leaving our options open on whether to castle kingside or queenside. Black has a good game. There are a lot more details in our Scotch Game chapter.  7…O-O  is also a safe option. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Four Knights Game"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
{ Before we get into the details of each variation, let's take a look at our preferred developing plan in most openings.   Already, after the first move it's pretty clear where most of our pieces want to go!   2.d4  This let's us demonstrate one of the points of 1...e5. We can just capture the pawn.  2...exd4  White will need to lose time recapturing on d4. Your opponent doesn't get an opportunity to take over the center. }
2... Nc6 { Black defends e5 and brings the knight to its best square. } 3. Nc3
{ White invites us to enter the Four Knights Game.   There's no better square for our g8-knight than f6, so let's go for it! }
3... Nf6
{ Another great square for a knight. The game won't stay symmetrical for long. }
4. d4
{ White opens the center, in the style of the Scotch Game.   4.Bb5  Bc5  As ususal, we're placing the bishop on c5 whenever possible.   This variation is called the Spanish Four Knights and that part of the Four Knights chapter demonstrates more details. }
4... exd4
{ We're usually not going to let White keep two pawns in the center. } 5. Nxd4
Bc5 { The best square for the bishop, as usual. } 6. Be3 Bb6
{ Like we saw in the Scotch, we will make sure that there's no tactic with Nxc6. The bishop is well protected on b6 and Black has good chances. You can learn more in the Four Knights chapter. Let's get going! }
