[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Italian: The Dubious 4.d4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. d4
{ This aggressive gambit is borderline unsound. I've found a surprising resource that should give Black an advantage in every line! }
4... Nxd4
{ The other two captures are much more popular, but this one is the best! } 5.
Be3
{ This may be best, but White has to work hard just to win back the sacrificed pawn. }
5... Qf6 6. Bxd4 exd4 7. e5 { Without this, Black just keeps the extra pawn. }
7... Qg6 8. O-O Ne7
{ We can't keep the extra pawn, but Black's bishop pair offers a small advantage. }
9. Nxd4 d5 { Black has a very comfortable game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Italian: The Ambitious 4.c3 / 5.d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. c3
{ This is White's most flexible option. Black must be ready for either a quick d2-d4 or the calmer d2-d3. Let's talk about some other options which won't be trainable:   4.O-O  Nf6  5.d4  Transposes to the 4. d4 line.   4.Nc3  This transposes into the 4.d3 line.  4...Nf6  5.d3  d6  And we're back in the Canal Variation.   4.Ng5  This is a good move against the Two Knights Defense, but after 3...Bc5 it just loses the game.  4...Qxg5  Black wins a piece! }
4... Nf6
{ Black continues to develop and attacks the e4-pawn. Now White can attack with d4 or defend with d3. }
5. d4
{ This was cutting edge theory in the romantic era of chess. These days good solutions have been found for Black in every line. }
5... exd4
{ The problem for White is that Black can meet cxd4 with a check.   White won't have time to build a powerful pawn center. }
6. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Black checks while the e4-pawn is still undefended. White can't keep control of the position. }
7. Bd2 { This is White's safest option, but Black also has nothing to fear. }
7... Bxd2+
{ The simplest solution is to trade pieces. White must recapture with a knight in order to defend e4. }
8. Nbxd2 d5 { Black breaks apart the white pawn center and has no problems. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Qb3 Nce7
{ At the top level, this is usually an invitation to a draw by repetition with  10...Na5  11.Qa4  Nc6  12.Qb3  Black is also happy to play 10...Nce7 instead and keep the fight going. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Italian: The Patient 4.c3 / 5.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. c3
{ This is White's most flexible option. Black must be ready for either a quick d2-d4 or the calmer d2-d3. Let's talk about some other options which won't be trainable:   4.O-O  Nf6  5.d4  is a dubious gambit covered in this line.   4.Nc3  This transposes into the 4.d3 line.  4...Nf6  5.d3  d6  And we're back in the Canal Variation.   4.Ng5  This is a good move against the Two Knights Defense, but after 3...Bc5 it just loses the game.  4...Qxg5  Black wins a piece! }
4... Nf6
{ Black continues to develop and attacks the e4-pawn. Now White can attack with d4 or defend with d3. }
5. d3
{ This is the most popular setup for White at the GM level. White hopes to play d4 at a useful moment later in the game. The b1-knight will head to d2 and most likely f1 and then e3 or g3.   In the meantime we will play d7-d6, castle the king and hide the bishop on the safe a7-square. This line is called the Giuoco Pianissimo @@StartBracket@@very quiet@@EndBracket@@ and the plans are more important than specific move orders. }
5... d6 { Black continues to develop and over-protects the e5-pawn. } 6. O-O a6
{ Some players prefer the pawn on a5, which takes more space but allows a white bishop to b5, pinning our knight in some variations.  Either way, we want to retreat our bishop to a7 so that d3-d4 won't come with an annoying threat. }
7. Nbd2
{ White continues the developing plan. With a pawn on c3, there's nowhere else for the knight to go. }
7... Ba7
{ Let's hide the bishop. Black now has the idea of grabbing the bishop pair with Na5. White typically avoids this with either Bb3 or a2-a4 to give the bishop an escape route.   The other big decision is whether White wants to play Re1 or h2-h3 first. As we will see, skipping the h-pawn advance gives Black some dangerous attacking ideas. }
8. Bb3
{ This is the old main line. Most top players these days prefer to create an escape route for the bishop by playing a2-a4. From a strategic standpoint it's not a huge difference. }
8... O-O { Let's secure the king before aiming for an attack. } 9. Re1
{ White hopes to save a tempo by avoiding h2-h3, but now Black can aim for a swift attack. }
9... Ng4 { The f2-pawn is vulnerable. } 10. Re2 Kh8
{ We are unpinning the f-pawn to prepare ...f7-f5. } 11. h3 Nh6
{ We don't want to block the f7-pawn. } 12. Nf1 f5
{ Black has a quick attack brewing with many pieces aiming towards the white king. }
