[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Spanish: Exchange Variation - 4.Bxc6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This brings us to the Ruy Lopez or Spanish Opening. This is the most popular way for White to meet 1...e5 at the top level and you'll see it frequently at the club level as well.   The bishop might capture the black knight at any moment and will pin the knight if the d7-pawn moves. Our simplest defense is to force the bishop to retreat. }
3... a6 { White can maintain control of the a4-e8 diagonal or exchange on c6. }
4. Bxc6
{ This is the Exchange Spanish. White hopes for an endgame where Black's doubled pawns will prove to be a disadvantage.   Fortunately, Black's two bishops offer full compensation for the damaged pawn structure and we are very far from the endgame. }
4... dxc6
{ In most positions it's best to capture toward the center, but this is a notable exception. Black frees the c8-bishop and the queen. }
5. Nxe5
{ This capture gives Black an easy game, but it's important to know how to win back your pawn. }
5... Qd4 { Black forks the white knight and the e4-pawn. } 6. Nf3 Qxe4+
{ Black wins back the pawn and prevents White from castling. } 7. Qe2 Qxe2+
{ White must recapture with the king and Black has a great position. } *

