[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Spanish: 5.O-O / 7.Nxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This brings us to the Ruy Lopez or Spanish Opening. This is the most popular way for White to meet 1...e5 at the top level and you'll see it frequently at the club level as well.   The bishop might capture the black knight at any moment and will pin the knight if the d7-pawn moves. Our simplest defense is to force the bishop to retreat. }
3... a6 { White can maintain control of the a4-e8 diagonal or exchange on c6. }
4. Ba4
{ White saves the bishop and maintains pressure on the c6-knight. Black should simply continue to develop. }
4... Nf6
{ Let's develop a piece and attack the e4-pawn. Just like last turn, White doesn't really threaten to win the e5-pawn yet. Now White has several option, which each take the game in a different direction. }
5. O-O
{ Historically, this is the main line of the Ruy Lopez. Black has several good options, but we're going to aim for our favorite setup. First, it helps to prevent White from getting any ideas of Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
5... b5 { Forcing the bishop to retreat. } 6. Bb3
{ Now we can develop our f8-bishop to its most active square. } 6... Bc5
{ This is the Archangle Variation of the Ruy Lopez. It's possibly Black's best way of playing for a win. Every piece soon reaches an active square. White has the the ability to build a big center with a quick c2-c3 and d2-d4, but Black's pieces will target those pawns and White won't have an easy life. }
7. Nxe5
{ White uses a fork trick to justify this knight sacrifice. It's reasonable for White, but shouldn't cause Black too much trouble. }
7... Nxe5 { There's no reason to avoid the direct recapture. } 8. d4
{ White uses a fork to win back the sacrificed piece. } 8... Bxd4
{ Black lures the white queen to a vulnerable position. } 9. Qxd4 d6
{ Black defends the knight on e5. Now White is the one who must be careful. }
10. f4
{ White can chase the knight from the center, but advancing the f-pawn also weakens the protection around White's king. }
10... Nc6 { Black saves the knight and gains time against the white queen. }
11. Qd3
{ White doesn't have any threats. Black can just secure the king with a good position. }
11... O-O
{ Black's plans include ...Re8 and ...Bb7 to target the e4-pawn.   If White allows it, we will also include ...Na5 to eliminate the active bishop on b3. }
