[Black "Scotch: 5.Be3 / 6.c3 Mainline "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { This move brings us to the Scotch Game. } 3... exd4
4. Nxd4
{ White aims to take over the center, but we can always target the vulnerable d4-knight.   4.c3  This move introduces the Goring Gambit. It's a close relative of the more popular Danish Gambit, so we will cover it there in the Odds and Ends chapter. }
4... Bc5
{ There's no reason to avoid our favorite setup with the bishop coming to c5. We gain a tempo on the knight and start eyeing the f2-pawn. }
5. Be3 { White defends the knight and prepares a clever trap. } 5... Qf6
{ Black continues to develop and attack d4-knight and f2-pawn. The queen also steps out of the way of the sort of nasty tactic that would occur after 5... Nf6 instead.   5...Nf6  This natural move already loses a piece.  6.Nxc6  bxc6  The queen is in danger so Black must recapture.  7.Bxc5  White wins a bishop. This explains why our queen is heading to f6. }
6. c3
{ White's best bet is to support the knight. On the the other hand, this takes away the c3-square from the knight on b1, while Black can continue to develop. }
6... Nge7 { With f6 occupied this is the best square for the g8-knight. } 7.
Bc4
{ Black has several options here. Let's keep White guessing which way we're going to castle for the moment and get ready to target the center with the c8-bishop. }
7... b6
{ From b7 the bishop will soon target the e4-pawn and potentially the white kingside as well. }
8. O-O
{ Now Black has a big choice.   We're going to call the safest move, castling our main line, but  8...Bb7  ,  keeping the option of ...O-O-O open, is a more double-edged option. }
8... O-O
{ This is the simplest path to a good position. Let's just get the king safe.   There's no need to learn variations past this point. Black is about to play ...Bb7 to connect the rooks and keep a good position. }
