[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Scotch Four Knights: 6.Nxc6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. d4
{ This move starts the Scotch Four Knights. It's a popular attempt at all levels for White to keep the game simple and press for a minute advantage. }
4... exd4
{ Black shouldn't try the passive defense with  4...d7-d6  ,  so trading pawns on d4 is the only choice. }
5. Nxd4
{ White recaptures. Now, the most common move is Bb4 to pin the c3-knight. However, our standard setup with ...Bc5 is a good option in this position too! }
5... Bc5
{ There's no need to avoid our favorite setup. We attack the knight on d4 and prepare threats against f2 in the long run. }
6. Nxc6
{ This is a reasonable capture, although it's much less popular than  6.Be3  .   6.Nb3  This transposes to thePotter Variation of the Scotch. }
6... bxc6
{ We don't want to trade queens on d8, so let's capture toward the center. } 7.
Bd3
{ White develops and firmly defends the e4-pawn.   Let's get our king safe. }
7... O-O
{ Black gets the king safe and we're ready to pin the e4-pawn with our rook. }
8. O-O Re8
{ Even when it's not a pin, it's useful to target the white e-pawn and prevent it from safely advancing. }
9. Bg5
{ White can pin the knight, but this isn't a big worry. The first step is to attack the bishop, which gives us the option of eventually playing ...g7-g5 later if we need to. }
9... h6 { Forcing White's bishop to retreat. } 10. Bh4
{ White can maintain the pin, but the bishop has a bit less room to move on the e1-h4 diagonal than it had on the longer c1-h6 line. }
10... Rb8
{ Let's take advantage of the half-open file and develop our rook with a threat. }
11. Rb1
{ White defends. Now Black has a pleasant choice between opening the position and sparking complications or breaking the pin on the f6-knight and playing a balanced game. }
11... Be7
{ This is the calm move. Black is ready to play ...d6 or ...d5 soon with a very safe position. }
