6. Be3
{ White develops, protects the knight on d4 and creates a serious threat. Black needs to remember the next move. }
6... Bb6
{ White threatened to capture on c6 and then win the bishop on c5, so we retreat the bishop to a defended square. }
7. Qd2 { White keeps developing and prepares to castle queenside. } 7... O-O
{ Let's get the king safe. } 8. Nxc6
{ White can choose this moment to exchange on c6. As usualy, we won't allow a trade of queens. }
8... bxc6 { Let's take toward the center and keep queens on the board. } 9.
O-O-O
{ Opposite side castling shouldn't be a problem. We already have a half-open file to start an attack. }
9... Qe7 { Black targets e4 and avoids a pin on the d-pawn. } 10. f3
{ White protects the e4-pawn, but now the e3-bishop is poorly defended and Black has a strong pawn break. }
10... d5
{ The e4-pawn is pinned against the e3-bishop and Black is doing well. } *

