[Black "King's Gambit: 2.f4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. f4
{ This is the romantic King's Gambit. White sacrifices a pawn and opens the kingside, but often creates wild complications.   2.Bc4  The Bishop's Opening is perfectly sound, but will nearly always transpose to one of our other openings.  2...Nc6  Black develops toward the center.  3.Qh5  This transposes to the Wayward Queen Attack.   2.Bc4  Nc6  3.d3  Nf6  At this point the game will almost always transpose to one of our other openings.  4.Nf3  is an Italian and  4.Nc3  is a Vienna. }
2... Bc5
{ Let's try to calm the King's Gambit with this safe developing move. It's quite an annoying one for a gambiteer to face. Black refuses to give up the center and makes it difficult for White to ever castle. }
3. Nf3 { White develops and builds pressure on the e5-pawn. } 3... d6
{ Black supports the center and prepares to develop the c8-bishop. } 4. c3
{ This is White's most ambitious try. White plans for d2-d4 to take over the center. On the other hand, he or she will have to defend it against threats from our pieces. }
4... Nf6 { Let's develop and eye the e4-pawn. } 5. d4
{ White forces our bishop to retreat, but that's another pawn that must be defended. }
5... exd4
{ It's useful to trade so that we don't need to defend the e5-pawn any longer. }
6. cxd4 { White chases the bishop. } 6... Bb6
{ We don't want to check because White would force a trade of bishops. From b6 the bishop can keep pressure on the d4-pawn. }
7. Nc3 { White defends e4. } 7... O-O
{ Black castles quickly and gets ready to attack on the e-file. } 8. Bd3
{ This gives us tme to break apart the white center. } 8... c5
{ Black will re-open the g1-a7 diagonal and White struggles to ever find a safe spot for the king. }
*

