[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Wayward Queen Attack: 2.Qh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. Qh5
{ This is officially called the Wayward Queen Attack. More commonly it's called the Scholars Mate. You definitely want to decline getting checkmated and get a good position. }
2... Nc6 { Let's defend the e5-pawn and develop a piece. } 3. Bc4
{ Now White wants to checkmate on f7. Obviously, we shouldn't let them. } 3...
g6 { Black blocks mate and gains time by attacking the white queen. } 4. Qf3
{ White still wants to checkmate. } 4... Nf6
{ Let's block the checkmate and develop another knight. } 5. Ne2
{ If White is serious about playing a real chess game after this ridiculous opening, this is the way to do it. Now we don't get Nd4 to target the white queen. }
5... Bg7 { Black develops another piece and prepares to castle. } 6. d3 d6
{ Black is ready to castle and can grab the bishop pair with Na5. The game is even and even Magnus Carlsen couldn't prove otherwise in Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2882@@EndBracket@@ -Dominguez Perez,L @@StartBracket@@2763@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Italian Game"]
[Black "Typical Attack on f2: Jonny2193 vs. PracticeMakesOK, Chess.com Blitz, 2024"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is a master-level blitz game between two anonymous players. I'm including it in order to demonstrate the types of powerful attacking ideas Black can generate by targeting the f2-pawn in the Italian. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3
{ With the move, White makes it clear that we're going to get a slower paced opening. White wants to gradually build up and prepare the d3-d4 push. }
5... a6 { Black establishes a retreat square for the c5-bishop. } 6. O-O Ba7
{ Now d4 won't come with any threats and Black has a free hand to react to that eventual advance the best way. }
7. a4
{ White usually will play this move or  7.Bb3  . That way the bishop can't get trapped by Black's knight with Na5. }
7... d6
{ Black protects e5 a second time and clears a path for the c8-bishop to develop. }
8. Bb3
{ This retreat isn't entirely needed, although it's not bad. The bishop may be heading to c2 soon.  8.Nbd2  would be more consistent with White's a4 advance. }
8... O-O
{ Black secures the king. Now White chooses whether to include the h2-h3 advance or try to get away without it. }
9. Re1
{ 9.h3  This rules out Black's attacking idea that we'll see in this game. Black continues to develop and may target the h3-pawn.  9...Be6  We're always happy to exchange on e6 and clear the f-file to attack with our rooks. }
9... Ng4 { Black targets the f2-pawn and aims for a quick attack. } 10. d4
{ 10.Re2  This is a more common defensive resource. Often in similar positions White will have already played Nbd2 and the d3-d4 move isn't playable.  10...Kh8!  This is Black's standard attacking idea. Black unpins the f-pawn and prepares f7-f5.  11.h3  Nh6  Again, supporting f5 to open the kingside. Black doesn't fear the exchange on h6.  12.Bxh6  gxh6  13.Nbd2  f5  Black has a powerful initiative. }
10... exd4 11. cxd4
{ This natural move allows a powerful attack!   11.Bg5!  This surprising move is necesary for White, forcing Black to withdraw the g4-knight.  11...Nf6   11...d3?!  This insane queen sacrifice is actually playable, but why try that when your position is already good?  12.Bxd8  Nxf2  Black's attack should eventually win back the queen with an OK game.  12.cxd4  Bg4  Black has strong pressure on the white center, but only a small advantage. }
11... Nxd4 { Black's pressure on f2 allows this surprising resource. } 12. Nxd4
Qh4 { White can't defend both h2 and f2. } 13. Be3
{ This is White's best defensive try, although it shouldn't be enough.   13.Nf3??  The most obvious move in the position actually allows a quick mate!  13...Qxf2+  14.Kh1  Qg1+!!  15.Rxg1  Nf2  Let me know if you ever get to play this amazing smothered mate in a game! }
13... Qxh2+ 14. Kf1 Qh1+ 15. Ke2 Qxg2
{ Black already has three pawns for a knight and White's centralized king will probably allow Black to win a pawn or two more. }
16. Rg1 Nxe3 { A nice counter-attack. White has to capture with the king! } 17.
Kxe3 { 17.Rxg2  Nxd1  18.Kxd1  Bxd4  Black wins material. } 17... Bxd4+
{ Black simplifies to an endgame with too many pawns for a knight. } 18. Kxd4
Qxf2+ { Pawn number four. } 19. Kc3 Be6
{ As usual, Black doesn't mind an exchange on e6 to open the f-file. That said,  19...Qe3+  , forking the king and the e4-pawn is even better. }
20. Nd2 Qe3+ { Black doesn't need another invitation to win the e-pawn. } 21.
Kc2 Bxb3+ { White must recapture with the knight, which costs one more pawn. }
22. Nxb3 Qxe4+ { That's five pawns for the knight! } 23. Qd3
{ Black can keep queens on the board and try to attack White's exposed king, but in a blitz game, simplifying to a winning endgame makes sense. }
23... Qxd3+ 24. Kxd3
{ The rest of the game is presented without comment. It was played at a fast pace and isn't relevant to the opening. Obviously, Black's five extra pawns are more valuable than the white knight! }
24... Rae8 25. Nd4 Re5 26. Rae1 Rfe8 27. Rxe5 dxe5 28. Nf5 g6 29. Ne3 c6 30.
Nc4 f5 31. Ke3 Re7 32. Rd1 Kg7 33. Nb6 h5 34. Rd7 Kf6 35. Rxe7 Kxe7 36. Nc4 Ke6
37. Na5 b5 38. axb5 cxb5 39. Nc6 h4 40. Nb4 a5 41. Nc6 a4 42. Na7 b4 43. Nb5 h3
44. Kf3 g5 45. Kg3 g4 46. Na7 a3 47. bxa3 bxa3 48. Nc6 a2 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
