1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. b4
{ A century and a half ago the Evans Gambit was a fearsome opening. Today, there are several solid responses. Let's learn one of the safest ones. }
4... Bxb4
{ Black must take the pawn. Other responses give White great chances for an edge. We are going to get a comfortable game by capturing the pawn and then giving it back at the right moment. }
5. c3
{ White wants to target the bishop and build a big center, so we're going to find a safe square to put it. }
5... Be7
{ There's no way for White to target the bishop here. It also rules out Ng5 any time soon. }
6. d4 Na5
{ This is our thematic idea against the Evans Gambit. We're happy to give back the extra pawn on e5 in order to get the bishop pair. }
7. Bd3
{ This is White's way of keeping the game complicated. Black still has nothing to fear. We will give back the extra pawn for smooth development. }
7... d6 { Black aims to simply develop the c8-bishop. } 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Nxe5
{ White has equalized material, but Black has the better pawn structure and doesn't face any significant challenges. }
9... Nf6 10. O-O O-O
{ There's no need to learn past this position. Black simply has the better pawn structure and good development. }
