[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. O-O Nf6 5. d4
{ If White insists on playing this borderline unsound gambit, then at least this is the most effective move order. }
5... Bxd4
{ The only good move.  5...Nxd4  would drop the e5-pawn and  5...exd4  allows the dangerous e4-e5 advance. }
6. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Now White has too moves to try to justify the pawn sacrifice. The key idea is to pin the f6-knight and open the f-file. Black will often give back the pawn and keep a small advantage. }
7. f4
{ White aims to open the f-file and then quickly pin the f6-knight.   7.Bg5  Qe7!?  This clever move forces White to change plans. If the f2-pawn advances then Qc5 will set up a deadly discovered check.  8.Nc3  White aims for Nd5, but that's easily prevented.   8.f4??  Qc5  This is the point of our early Qe7. White has no good defense against the threats of Qxc4 and discovered checks from the d4-knight.  8...c6  Covering the d5-square.  9.f4  d6  Simple and strong.   9...Qc5?!  This allows the sort of crazy complications that White is aiming for.  10.Bxf7+!  Kxf7  11.fxe5  The game is about equal, but why bother with this mess?  10.fxe5  dxe5  11.Bxf6  gxf6  White has managed to double Black's f-pawns, but there's no attack and Black is still ahead by a pawn.  12.Kh1  Rg8  The half-open g-file gives Black attacking chances. White would be lucky to hold a draw from this tough position. }
7... d6 { We can simply defend the e5-pawn. } 8. fxe5 dxe5 9. Bg5
{ The pin is annoying, but Black is up a pawn and actually has the safer king as well. }
9... Qe7
{ Black threatens Qc5+, preparing a deadly discovered check and attacking the c4-bishop. }
10. Na3
{ White defends the bishop on c4, but this isn't a great square for a knight.   10.c3  hite can force the knight to retreat, but will still be left fighting to regain the sacrificed pawn.  10...Ne6  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.Kh1  White has to waste time with the king to avoid a fork on c5.  12...Nf4  White must further weaken the kingside if he or she aims to unblock the f-file and regain the lost pawn.  13.g3  Nh3  14.Qh5  Ng5  The knight targets e4 and keeps f7 well defended.  15.Nd2  Bh3  Black is fully developed and ready to castle queenside. White still hasn't regained the sacrificed pawn. }
10... Ne6
{ White would soon attack the knight anyway. We can retreat and hit the bishop on g5. }
11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Qf3
{ White wants to win back the pawn on f6, but we don't have to let it be easy. }
12... Nf4 13. g3 Nh3+ { Gaining time on the vulnerable white king. } 14. Kh1
Ng5 { Black frees h3 for the bishop and eyes the e4-pawn. } 15. Qxf6 Qxf6 16.
Rxf6 Bh3
{ Material is even, but the e4-pawn is weak and Black is the only one with winnning chances. }
