4. c3
{ This is White's most flexible option. Black must be ready for either a quick d2-d4 or the calmer d2-d3. Let's talk about some other options which won't be trainable:   4.O-O  Nf6  5.d4  Transposes to the 4. d4 line.  5...Bxd4   4.Nc3  This transposes into the 4.d3 line.  4...Nf6  5.d3  d6  And we're back in the Canal Variation.   4.Ng5  This is a good move against the Two Knights Defense, but after 3...Bc5 it just loses the game.  4...Qxg5  Black wins a piece! }
4... Nf6
{ Black continues to develop and attacks the e4-pawn. Now White can attack with d4 or defend with d3. }
5. d4
{ This was cutting edge theory in the romantic era of chess. These days good solutions have been found for Black in every line. }
5... exd4
{ The problem for White is that Black can meet cxd4 with a check.   White won't have time to build a powerful pawn center. }
6. e5
{ This line has become popular in the last few years, but Black can get a good game by aiming for active pieces. Step one is to counterattack in the center. }
6... d5
{ This is a good idea to remember. Instead of moving the knight, we chase White's bishop from the center. }
7. Bb5 Ne4
{ Knights are great in the center. White can win back the sacrificed pawn, but it won't be enough for an advantage. }
8. cxd4 Bb6 { Black keeps pressure on the d4-pawn. } 9. Nc3
{ White has no immediate threats, so Black can get a good game by developing quickly. }
9... O-O 10. Be3 Bg4
{ This pin makes White have to be careful about defending d4. } 11. h3 Bh5
{ It's useful to keep the pin going intead of capturing right away. } 12. Qc2
Nxc3 13. bxc3
{ Black's only problem is White's strong pawn center, but one pawn break takes care of that. }
13... f6 14. exf6 Qxf6 { Black has good development and full equality. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Italian Game"]
[Black "Italian: The Ambitious 4.c3 / 5.d4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. c3
{ This is White's most flexible option. Black must be ready for either a quick d2-d4 or the calmer d2-d3. Let's talk about some other options which won't be trainable:   4.O-O  Nf6  5.d4  Transposes to the 4. d4 line.  5...Bxd4   4.Nc3  This transposes into the 4.d3 line.  4...Nf6  5.d3  d6  And we're back in the Canal Variation.   4.Ng5  This is a good move against the Two Knights Defense, but after 3...Bc5 it just loses the game.  4...Qxg5  Black wins a piece! }
4... Nf6
{ Black continues to develop and attacks the e4-pawn. Now White can attack with d4 or defend with d3. }
5. d4
{ This was cutting edge theory in the romantic era of chess. These days good solutions have been found for Black in every line. }
5... exd4
{ The problem for White is that Black can meet cxd4 with a check.   White won't have time to build a powerful pawn center. }
6. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Black checks while the e4-pawn is still undefended. White can't keep control of the position. }
7. Nc3
{ If White has one more turn to defend the pawn center then Black would be in trouble. As it is, Black wins a pawn and White may have a hard time showing compensation. }
7... Nxe4 { Black wins a key pawn. } 8. O-O Bxc3
{ If White recaptures then ...d7-d5 would give Black a great game.   White must play aggressively to stay in the game. }
9. d5 Bf6 { Let's save the strong bishop. } 10. Re1
{ The e4-knight is doomed, so let's save the other one. } 10... Ne7 11. Rxe4 d6
{ Black is ready to castle and keep an extra pawn. } 12. Bg5 Bxg5
{ There's no reason to avoid this exchange. } 13. Nxg5 h6
{ 13...O-O  14.Nxh7  White has a scary attack. } 14. Qe2
{ White can build an impressive battery on the e-file, but Black can simply take the knight and follow our formula of capturing material and then giving it back at the right moment. }
14... hxg5 15. Re1
{ Black is ahead by a piece and a pawn. By giving the piece back, we can end the White attack and keep a clear extra pawn. }
15... Be6
{ An awesome idea! Black gives the bishop to completely close the e-file. } 16.
dxe6 f6
{ Every white piece is blocked by the immobile e6-pawn.   17.Re3  c6  Letting the queen develop.  18.Rh3  Rxh3  19.gxh3  g6  Preventing the check on h5.  20.Qf3  Qa5  Black attacks the rook and gains a tempo for Qf5. White has no compensation for Black's extra pawn. }
