5. d3
{ This is the most popular setup for White at the GM level. White hopes to play d4 at a useful moment later in the game. The b1-knight will head to d2 and most likely f1 and then e3 or g3.   In the meantime we will play d7-d6, castle the king and hide the bishop on the safe a7-square. This line is called the Guicco Pianisimo @@StartBracket@@very quiet@@EndBracket@@ and the plans are more important than specific move orders. }
5... d6 { Black continues to develop and over-protects the e5-pawn. } 6. O-O a6
{ Some players prefer the pawn on a5, which takes more space but allows a white bishop to b5, pinning our knight in some variations.  Either way, we want to retreat our bishop to a7 so that d3-d4 won't come with an annoying threat. }
7. Nbd2
