{ This is White's most flexible option. Black must be ready for either a quick d2-d4 or the calmer d2-d3. Let's talk about some other options which won't be trainable:   4.O-O  Nf6  5.d4  Transposes to the 4. d4 line.  5...Bxd4   4.Nc3  This transposes into the 4.d3 line.  4...Nf6  5.d3  d6  And we're back in the Canal Variation.   4.Ng5  This is a good move against the Two Knights Defense, but after 3...Bc5 it just loses the game.  4...Qxg5  Black wins a piece! }
4... Nf6
{ Black continues to develop and attacks the e4-pawn. Now White can attack with d4 or defend with d3. }
5. d3
{ This is the most popular setup for White at the GM level. White hopes to play d4 at a useful moment later in the game. The b1-knight will head to d2 and most likely f1 and then e3 or g3.   In the meantime we will play d7-d6, castle the king and hide the bishop on the safe a7-square. This line is called the Guicco Pianisimo @@StartBracket@@very quiet@@EndBracket@@ and the plans are more important than specific move orders. }
5... d6 { Black continues to develop and over-protects the e5-pawn. } 6. O-O a6
{ Some players prefer the pawn on a5, which takes more space but allows a white bishop to b5, pinning our knight in some variations.  Either way, we want to retreat our bishop to a7 so that d3-d4 won't come with an annoying threat. }
7. Nbd2
{ White continues the developing plan. With a pawn on c3, there's nowhere else for the knight to go. }
7... Ba7
{ Let's hide the bishop. Black now has the idea of grabbing the bishop pair with Na5. White typically avoids this with either Bb3 or a2-a4 to give the bishop an escape route.   The other big decision is whether White wants to play Re1 or h2-h3 first. As we will see, skipping the h-pawn advance gives Black some dangerous attacking ideas. }
8. Bb3
{ This is the old main line. Most top players these days prefer to create an escape route for the bishop by playing a2-a4. From a strategic standpoint it's not a huge difference. }
8... O-O { Let's secure the king before aiming for an attack. } 9. h3
{ White prevents ...Ng4, so we'll need to build an initiative another way. Black aims to exchange bishops on e6 to open the f-file and prepare a kingside attack. }
9... Be6 10. Re1
{ White ignores the bishop, but Black can just trade with no worries. } 10...
Bxb3 11. axb3 { This lets Black break in the center. } 11... d5 12. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black has a very active position. } *

