[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Italian Game"]
[Black "Italian: Canal Variation - 4.d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. d3
{ This is a flexible choice for White, who doesn't tell us yet if a piece or a pawn will occupy c3. }
4... Nf6
{ The knight heads to its best square and Black prepares to castle. What more could you want in one move? }
5. Nc3
{ This line introduces the Canal Variation. It's a symmetrical opening that's very popular at the club level. Despite its apparent simplicity, both sides must be careful. All the pieces are still on the board, so there's no reason to assume that symetry will mean a quick draw. }
5... d6
{ We're only going to copy for one more move. Black wants the option of pinning the f3-knight. }
6. O-O
{ This is playable, but a practical mistake. The pin on the f3-knight is much more dangerous once the king is already committed to the kingside. }
6... Bg4 { The pin is dangerous once White has castled. } 7. h3 Bh5
{ If you can play ...Nd4 next, White will run into trouble.   Meanwhile, g4 to break the pin is serious commitment that will permanently expose White's king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Italian Game"]
[Black "Italian: Canal Variation - 4.d3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. d3
{ This is a flexible choice for White, who doesn't tell us yet if a piece or a pawn will occupy c3. }
4... Nf6
{ The knight heads to its best square and Black prepares to castle. What more could you want in one move? }
5. Nc3
{ This line introduces the Canal Variation. It's a symmetrical opening that's very popular at the club level. Despite its apparent simplicity, both sides must be careful. All the pieces are still on the board, so there's no reason to assume that symetry will mean a quick draw. }
5... d6
{ We're only going to copy for one more move. Black wants the option of pinning the f3-knight. }
6. Bg5
{ This pin can be dangerous if Black's not careful. It's hard to escape without damaging the kingside pawn structure. }
6... h6
{ It's essential to break the pin before we castle.   6...O-O  This is an instructive mistake. If you put your king on the kingside and allow White to target the pinned knight, there's a good chance that you'll get checkmated in a miniature.  7.Nd5  White is ready to capture on f6 and force Black to recapture with the g7-pawn. The following line isn't forced, but it's an example of the sort of disaster that you'll want to avoid.  7...Be6  8.Nxf6+  gxf6  9.Bh6  The bishop attacks Black's rook and aims to help out with a checkmate on the g-file.  9...Re8  10.Nh4  White makes room for the queen to reach the kingside. Black is in serious trouble.  10...Kh8  Black prepares ...Rg8 and has chances to fight back in this tough position.   10...Ne7  It looks logical to bring the knight to cover f5 and g6, but it just doesn't work out here.  11.Bxe6  White trades off a key defender and soon checkmates.  11...fxe6  12.Qg4+  Black can't stop mate for long.  12...Ng6  13.Nxg6  f5  This is as good a try as any, but White can use a double check to force mate.  14.Ne7+  Kf7  15.Qg7  OK. Now we know what to avoid! Let's check out a better defense, where we break the pin instead of castling. }
7. Bh4
{ White maintains the pin, but Black hasn't castled yet and has a surprising resourse. }
7... g5
{ Since our king isn't committed to the kingside there's no real downside to this advance. White's bishop will be extremely passive on g3 where it has no safe moves. }
8. Nxg5
{ This sacrifice might look scary, but when Black's not castled yet, White doesn't have enough compensation for the knight. }
8... hxg5 9. Bxg5 Rg8
{ The rook attacks White's bishop and prepares to defend the pinned knight from g6. }
10. h4 Bb4
{ Black pins the knight so White won't be able to play Nd5. White's attack soon runs out of steam. }
11. Qf3 Rg6
{ Black will play ...Nd4 next to chase the White queen away.   Soon Black's material advantage should tell. }
*

