[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Italian Game"]
[Black "Italian: Canal Variation - 4.d3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. d3
{ This is a flexible choice for White, who doesn't tell us yet if a piece or a pawn will occupy c3. }
4... Nf6
{ The knight heads to its best square and Black prepares to castle. What more could you want in one move? }
5. Nc3
{ This line introduces the Canal Variation. It's a symmetrical opening that's very popular at the club level. Despite its apparent simplicity, both sides must be careful. All the pieces are still on the board, so there's no reason to assume that symetry will mean a quick draw. }
5... d6
{ We're only going to copy for one more move. Black wants the option of pinning the f3-knight. }
6. Bg5
{ This pin can be dangerous if Black's not careful. It's hard to escape without damaging the kingside pawn structure. }
6... h6
{ It's essential to break the pin before we castle.   6...O-O  This is an instructive mistake. If you put your king on the kingside and allow White to target the pinned knight, there's a good chance that you'll get checkmated in a miniature.  7.Nd5  White is ready to capture on f6 and force Black to recapture with the g7-pawn. The following line isn't forced, but it's an example of the sort of disaster that you'll want to avoid.  7...Be6  8.Nxf6+  gxf6  9.Bh6  The bishop attacks Black's rook and aims to help out with a checkmate on the g-file.  9...Re8  10.Nh4  White makes room for the queen to reach the kingside. Black is in serious trouble.  10...Kh8  Black prepares ...Rg8 and has chances to fight back in this tough position.   10...Ne7  It looks logical to bring the knight to cover f5 and g6, but it just doesn't work out here.  11.Bxe6  White trades off a key defender and soon checkmates.  11...fxe6  12.Qg4+  Black can't stop mate for long.  12...Ng6  13.Nxg6  f5  This is as good a try as any, but White can use a double check to force mate.  14.Ne7+  Kf7  15.Qg7  OK. Now we know what to avoid! Let's check out a better defense, where we break the pin instead of castling. }
7. Bxf6
{ White can't maintain the pin, so the best move is to gain time by luring Black's queen to a vulnerable square. In exchange, Black wins the bishop pair, which is enough to keep a comfortable position. }
7... Qxf6 8. Nd5
{ White attacks the black queen and the c7-pawn, but we can defend. } 8... Qd8
{ The only safe move, but not a hard one to find. } 9. c3
{ Here we see the main imbalance in the Canal Variation. White will be able to build a big center with d3-d4, but Black's bishop pair is equally relevant and leads to a balanced position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Italian Game"]
[Black "When White Doesn't Castle: Ynojosa Aponte, F. vs. Hakobyan, A. Pan American Rapid Ch. 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's check out a game between IM Felix Jose Ynojosa Aponte and GM Aram Hakobyan. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This introduces the Italian Variation. It's popular at all levels of chess. White develops and attacks the f7-pawn. }
3... Bc5
{ Black immediately reaches our favorite setup. We eye the f2-pawn and take firm control of the d4-square. It's also nice that the queen covers the g5-square so White has no way to start an easy attack.   Now, White has a wide set of choices.  4.d3  ,  4.c3  ,  4.O-O  ,  4.b4!?  ,  4.d4?!  and  4.Nc3  all make some sense.   3...Nf6  The Two Knights Defense is a good opening as well, but it allows White to target the f7-pawn, which requires a very precise response to avoid simply losing material.  4.Ng5 }
4. Nc3
{ This logical developing move is very popular at the club level. White just develops toward the center and Black does the same. }
4... Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. Bg5
{ This is the Canal Variation. It has a bit of a drawish reputation, but as we'll see here, that doesn't mean that there can't be fireworks. }
6... h6
{ Black breaks the pin right away.   6...Bg4?!  Black shouldn't copy forever.  7.Nd5  White is the first one to attack the pinned knight. Black has a hard time equalizing here. }
7. Bxf6
{ White doesn't want to lose time retreating the bishop.   7.Bh4  g5  Black has a comfortable game. Because Black isn't castled, the advanced pawns don't expose the king in any serious way. }
7... Qxf6 { Black recaptures without damaging the pawn structure. } 8. Nd5
{ This is White's idea. Black must retreat the queen to d8 to avoid losing material. }
8... Qd8 9. c3
{ White is ready to take over the center with the d3-d4 advance, but Black has the bishop pair and more than one way to equalize. }
9... Ne7 { Black aims to trade off White's well-placed knight. } 10. d4
{ White strikes first in the center. The game was symetrical a few moves earlier, but now it's getting exciting. }
10... exd4 { Black can't defend the e5-pawn, so this exchange makes sense. }
11. cxd4 Nxd5
{ Black removes the defender of the b4-square and threatens an annoying check. If White wants to castle, he needs to capture on c5. }
12. dxc5 Nf4
{ The knight is a powerful attacking piece on f4. White has to decide how to defend the g2-pawn. }
13. g3
{ 13.O-O  This is safe, but Black can either castle with an OK game or trade into a pleasant ending.  13...dxc5  White must trade queens to win back the pawn.  14.Qxd8+  Kxd8  15.Bxf7  White equalizes material, but Black is more active in the endgame.  15...Ke7  With queens off, the centralized king helps Black.  16.Bc4  Rd8  This ending is equal, but with competing pawn majorities, a draw is certainly not guarenteed. }
13... Nh3
{ The knight is annoying here, keeping White from castling.   13...Ng2+?  This tempting check just gets the knight trapped.  14.Ke2  Black can defend the knight with the bishop, but White should be able to win it eventually. It has no way to ever escape from g2. }
14. cxd6 O-O
{ There's no need to recapture on d6. White's king is stuck in the center at the moment and Black wants to catch it there as quickly as possible. }
15. dxc7
{ This is just too greedy. White's king is in the center and Black is happy to sacrifice a pawn to open lines.   15.Qd4  This is White's safest option. The queen defends f2 and White may even try castling queenside. }
15... Qxc7 { Gaining a tempo for the attack by spying the c4-bishop. } 16. Qd4
Re8 { Black develops and pins the e4-pawn. } 17. Kf1
{ This is relatively best, but giving up on castling is a clear sign that something has gone wrong for White. }
17... Bg4
{ Developing and gaining another tempo. Black's pawn sacrifice has worked out beatifully. }
18. Nd2 Rad8 { The final piece joins the attack. } 19. Bd5 Ng5
{ White is doomed on the light squares. e4, f3 and h3 are all vulnerable and Black is about to break through. }
20. Kg2
{ White's king tries to hide on the kingside. If he had time to develop the h1-rook on the next turn, then this might work. }
20... Bh3+ { White's king only has one safe square. } 21. Kg1 Rxe4
{ What a spectacular way to end the game! If White's queen or bishop captures on e4 then Black wins the queen. If White's knight captures on e4 then Nf3 comes with a pretty checkmate. White resigned here, but let's get the checmate on the board. }
22. Nxe4 Nf3# *

