[Black "Spanish: Exchange Variation - 4.Bxc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This brings us to the Ruy Lopez or Spanish Opening. This is the most popular way for White to meet 1...e5 at the top level and you'll see it frequently at the club level as well.   The bishop might capture the black knight at any moment and will pin the knight if the d7-pawn moves. Our simplest defense is to force the bishop to retreat. }
3... a6 { White can maintain control of the a4-e8 diagonal or exchange on c6. }
4. Bxc6
{ This is the Exchange Spanish. White hopes for an endgame where Black's doubled pawns will prove to be a disadvantage.   Fortunately, Black's two bishops offer full compensation for the damaged pawn structure and we are very far from the endgame. }
4... dxc6
{ In most positions it's best to capture toward the center, but this is a notable exception. Black frees the c8-bishop and the queen. }
5. O-O
{ Now White's Nxe5 threat is dangerous. The Qd4 fork that we saw last move doesn't work because of an upcoming pin on the e-file. Black has many moves here and we're going to go with the most aggressive option. }
5... Bg4 { Black pins the knight and sets a devilish trap. } 6. h3 h5
{ A beautiful fishing pole tactic. If White captures the bishop, Black has a vicious attack! }
7. hxg4
{ This is already a serious mistake. The open h-file toward the white king is worth more than a piece! }
7... hxg4 8. Ne1
{ It would actually be better for White to sacrifice the knight, but Black is doing well in either case. For the moment, let's see the point of Black's bishop sacrifice in its pure form. }
8... Qh4 { Black's battery on the h-file will soon lead to checkmate. } 9. f3
{ White tries to create an escape route for the king, but Black can lock the door. }
9... g3 { Black controls the f2-square and checkmates on the next move. } 10.
Rf2 Qh1# { A quick win! } *

