1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This brings us to the Ruy Lopez or Spanish Opening. This is the most popular way for White to meet 1...e5 at the top level and you'll see it frequently at the club level as well.   The bishop might capture the black knight at any moment and will pin the knight if the d7-pawn moves. Our simplest defense is to force the bishop to retreat. }
3... a6 { White can maintain control of the a4-e8 diagonal or exchange on c6. }
4. Ba4
{ White saves the bishop and maintains pressure on the c6-knight. Black should simply continue to develop. }
4... Nf6
{ Let's develop a piece and attack the e4-pawn. Just like last turn, White doesn't really threaten to win the e5-pawn yet. Now White has several option, which each take the game in a different direction. }
5. Nc3
{ This logical developing move has always been rare on the top level. The rule of thumb is that whenever the e4-pawn is defended, we need to prevent White from capturing on c6 and winning the e5-pawn.   This position is no exception. }
5... b5
{ Let's force the white bishop to retreat and then develop according to our favorite plan. }
6. Bb3 { The only safe square for the bishop. } 6... Bc5
{ Black has other options, but this is the most active square for the bishop. }
7. Nxe5 { This fork trick is playable for White, but not at all scary. } 7...
Nxe5
{ The only good move. Black won't be able to keep the extra piece, but that's OK. }
8. d4 Bxd4
{ This is the best way to return the piece. Black keeps a knight in the center and lures White's queen to a vulnerable position. }
9. Qxd4 d6
{ Black defends the knight and keeps a good position. White must watch out for ...c7-c5, followed by ...c5-c4 to trap the b3-bishop.   White's the one that must play carefully to demonstrate equality. }
