[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Spanish Opening"]
[Black "Spanish: Delayed Exchange - 5.Bxc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This brings us to the Ruy Lopez or Spanish Opening. This is the most popular way for White to meet 1...e5 at the top level and you'll see it frequently at the club level as well.   The bishop might capture the black knight at any moment and will pin the knight if the d7-pawn moves. Our simplest defense is to force the bishop to retreat. }
3... a6 { White can maintain control of the a4-e8 diagonal or exchange on c6. }
4. Ba4
{ White saves the bishop and maintains pressure on the c6-knight. Black should simply continue to develop. }
4... Nf6
{ Let's develop a piece and attack the e4-pawn. Just like last turn, White doesn't really threaten to win the e5-pawn yet. Now White has several option, which each take the game in a different direction. }
5. Bxc6
{ This is the Delayed Exchange Variation.   White argues that the black knight is misplaced on f6, compared to if White had captured on c6 last move. Most of us disagree with that assessment. }
5... dxc6
{ Capturing with the d-pawn allows Black to quickly develop the queen and the c8-bishop. }
6. d3
{ Once the e4-pawn is defended, White's threat to the e5-pawn becomes serious. }
6... Bd6
{ There's no need to make this complicated. Let's just develop and defend the e5-pawn. }
7. Nbd2
{ White's idea is to develop the knight to c4 and the c1-bishop to b2, in order to target the e5-pawn. Fortunately, Black can keep developing and counter White's plan without much trouble. }
7... Be6 { Black is happy to capture on c4 if the knight heads there. } 8. O-O
O-O
{ Black has no problems. We will continue a few more moves to demonstrate a strong middlegame plan. }
9. b3 Nd7
{ Believe it or not, this knight is heading all the way to d4! Black plans ...c6-c5, ...Nd7-b8-c6-d4. From there it will dominate the center. }
10. Bb2 c5
{ White has no way to aim for the e4-break. Before it continues its re-route the black knight helps protect the e5-pawn. }
11. a4 b6
{ We don't want to let White's pawn to a5 without being able to walk our b-pawn past it. }
12. Qe2 f6
{ Now the e-pawn is well defended and Black's knight is free to move. Keep in mind that Black is the only one with a light-squared bishop, so opening the a2-g8 diagonal isn't dangerous. }
13. Nc4 Nb8 { Continuing the plan. } 14. Ne3 Nc6
{ The knight is great on c6 and can reach d4 whenever it needs to.   Black is already slightly better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Spanish Opening"]
[Black "Spanish: 5.O-O / 7.Nxe5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This brings us to the Ruy Lopez or Spanish Opening. This is the most popular way for White to meet 1...e5 at the top level and you'll see it frequently at the club level as well.   The bishop might capture the black knight at any moment and will pin the knight if the d7-pawn moves. Our simplest defense is to force the bishop to retreat. }
3... a6 { White can maintain control of the a4-e8 diagonal or exchange on c6. }
4. Ba4
{ White saves the bishop and maintains pressure on the c6-knight. Black should simply continue to develop. }
4... Nf6
{ Let's develop a piece and attack the e4-pawn. Just like last turn, White doesn't really threaten to win the e5-pawn yet. Now White has several option, which each take the game in a different direction. }
5. O-O
{ Historically, this is the main line of the Ruy Lopez. Black has several good options, but we're going to aim for our favorite setup. First, it helps to prevent White from getting any ideas of Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
5... b5 { Forcing the bishop to retreat. } 6. Bb3
{ Now we can develop our f8-bishop to its most active square. } 6... Bc5
{ This is the Archangel Variation of the Ruy Lopez. It's possibly Black's best way of playing for a win. Every piece soon reaches an active square. White has the the ability to build a big center with a quick c2-c3 and d2-d4, but Black's pieces will target those pawns and White won't have an easy life. }
7. Nxe5
{ White uses a fork trick to justify this knight sacrifice. It's reasonable for White, but shouldn't cause Black too much trouble. }
7... Nxe5 { There's no reason to avoid the direct recapture. } 8. d4
{ White uses a fork to win back the sacrificed piece. } 8... Bxd4
{ Black lures the white queen to a vulnerable position. } 9. Qxd4 d6
{ Black defends the knight on e5. Now White is the one who must be careful. }
10. f4
{ White can chase the knight from the center, but advancing the f-pawn also weakens the protection around White's king. }
10... Nc6 { Black saves the knight and gains time against the white queen. }
11. Qd3
{ White doesn't have any threats. Black can just secure the king with a good position. }
11... O-O
{ Black's plans include ...Re8 and ...Bb7 to target the e4-pawn.   If White allows it, we will also include ...Na5 to eliminate the active bishop on b3. }
