{ Black lures the white queen to a vulnerable position. } 9. Qxd4 d6
{ Black defends the knight on e5. Now White is the one who must be careful. }
10. Bg5
{ This natural-looking move falls into an important trap that we should look for whenever the white queen is in the center. }
10... c5
{ Black gains a tempo on White's queen in order to trap the white bishop. } 11.
Bxf6
{ White hopes to distract the black queen to escpae the trapped piece, but there's no need to cooperate. }
11... gxf6 { 11...Qxf6  allows  12.Qd5  to gain time on the a8-rook. } 12. Qd5
Be6
{ Black keeps making threats and defends the a8-rook. We'll soon win material. }
13. Qd2 c4 { The bishop is trapped and Black should soon win the game. } *

