{ The knight aims for g6 in the near future. You don't really need to learn specific moves past this point, but let's take a look at a nice game by GM Josh Friedel with the Black pieces. }
10. Bc2 { White defends the e4-pawn. } 10... O-O
{ Black's in no rush. We can castle before determining how the c8-bishop will develop. }
11. h3 { White prevents ...Bg4, but the pawn may be a target on h3. } 11... Ng6
{ The knight eyes a great attacking outpost on f4. } 12. a4
{ White threatens axb5 because it would pin the a6-pawn. Black has several solutions, including ...Rb8.   GM Josh chooses another good option. }
12... Bd7 13. Na3 Qe8
{ The queen protects b5 and will potentially gain access to the kingside if the f-pawn advances. }
14. axb5 axb5 15. Bd3 Nh5
{ The knight heads to f4 and the f-pawn is ready to advance. } 16. Kh2 Nhf4
{ This is a great attacking square for a knight. White must watch out for sacrifices on g2 or h3. }
17. Bxf4 Nxf4 { Black simply replaces one knight with another one. } 18. Rb1 f5
{ Now the rook can join the attack. } 19. g3
{ White forces the knight to move, but Black has a short combination to win material. }
19... Nxd3 20. Qxd3 fxe4
{ White resigned in Pacchiana,D @@StartBracket@@1824@@EndBracket@@ -Friedel,J @@StartBracket@@2233@@EndBracket@@ Manchester 2002.   Black can meet  21.Qxe4  with  21...Bf5  to skewer and win an exchange. }
