[White "2) Spanish Opening"]
[Black "Spanish: Mainline with 9.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This brings us to the Ruy Lopez or Spanish Opening. This is the most popular way for White to meet 1...e5 at the top level and you'll see it frequently at the club level as well.   The bishop might capture the black knight at any moment and will pin the knight if the d7-pawn moves. Our simplest defense is to force the bishop to retreat. }
3... a6 { White can maintain control of the a4-e8 diagonal or exchange on c6. }
4. Ba4
{ White saves the bishop and maintains pressure on the c6-knight. Black should simply continue to develop. }
4... Nf6
{ Let's develop a piece and attack the e4-pawn. Just like last turn, White doesn't really threaten to win the e5-pawn yet. Now White has several option, which each take the game in a different direction. }
5. O-O
{ Historically, this is the main line of the Ruy Lopez. Black has several good options, but we're going to aim for our favorite setup. First, it helps to prevent White from getting any ideas of Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
5... b5 { Forcing the bishop to retreat. } 6. Bb3
{ Now we can develop our f8-bishop to its most active square. } 6... Bc5
{ This is the Archangel Variation of the Ruy Lopez. It's possibly Black's best way of playing for a win. Every piece soon reaches an active square. White has the the ability to build a big center with a quick c2-c3 and d2-d4, but Black's pieces will target those pawns and White won't have an easy life. }
7. c3
{ White prepares d2-d4 to build a strong pawn center. This is virtually the only line in our whole repertoire where we're going to let White control the center like that.   Fortunately, all of Black's pieces are active and we're going to cause White serious headaches trying to keep those center pawns protected. }
7... d6
{ Black prepares to develop the c8-bishop and adds another defender to the e5-pawn. }
8. d4 { White attacks the bishop, but it can comfortably retreat. } 8... Bb6
{ The bishop is well placed on b6, where the c7-pawn can protect it and it eyes the d4-pawn. This is a critical position for the Archangel Variation of the Ruy Lopez. White has several plans, but none of them will cause us too much trouble. Black's goals are generally going to be to caste and then play Bg4 if allowed to pin the f3-knight. If White prevents Bg4 with h2-h3, then the bishop will be well placed on b7, eyeing the e4-pawn. It's important to notice that Black can only rarely capture the e4-pawn going forward because Bd5 will fork both black knights. We don't want to fall into that trap! }
9. a4
{ This is White's most aggressive challenge to Black's setup. The immediate threat is axb5, which would pin the a6-pawn and win material. Black can solve the problem by developing the c8-bishop, but the simplest solution is ...Rb8, just stepping off the a-file entirely. }
9... Rb8
{ Black avoids any pins on the a-file and supports the b5-pawn if the b6-bishop ever moves. }
10. a5
{ This is a tricky attacking idea, but Black is OK with careful defense. }
10... Ba7
{ Black can't safely capture the a5-pawn, but the bishop is secure on a7 now that White has no way to open the a-file.   10...Nxa5  This capture allows White a dangerous sacrifice.  11.Rxa5  Bxa5  12.dxe5  Nxe4  This almost works, but there's a tactical flaw.   12...dxe5  doesn't work either after  13.Qxd8+  Kxd8  14.Nxe5  .  13.Qd5  Be6  Black defends f7 and skewers to win the bishop on b3.  14.Qxe4  Bxb3  15.Nd4  Ouch! White attacks b3 and also aims to fork three different black pieces with Nc6. Black's in trouble.   10...Bxa5??  11.d5  Black loses a piece. }
11. Be3
{ White secures the d4-pawn and sets up potential discovery tactics based on the d4-d5 advance. }
11... Bg4
{ Black pins the knight, which increases the pressure against the d4-pawn. }
12. Nbd2 O-O
{ This is the most practical move. Black secures the king and now threatens to win the d4-pawn.   12...exd4  By itself this move is playable, but let's not get greedy and fall into a trap.  13.cxd4  Nxd4?  The pawn is poisoned for the moment.    14.Bxd4  Bxd4  15.Bxf7+!  If Black's king recaptures, then White can escape the pin.  15...Kxf7  16.Qb3+  d5  17.Nxd4  White wins back the sacrificed piece and keeps the much safer king. }
13. h3
{ White can force the bishop to retreat, but it's even stronger to insert a capture first. }
13... exd4
{ Black clears the e-file to make sure that White won't have any well timed d4-d5 tactics. }
14. cxd4 Bh5
{ The bishop retreats and maintains the pin. White's center is under serious pressure and Black can add more attackers against the e-pawn with moves like ...Re8 and ...Bg6. }
