1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This brings us to the Ruy Lopez or Spanish Opening. This is the most popular way for White to meet 1...e5 at the top level and you'll see it frequently at the club level as well.   The bishop might capture the black knight at any moment and will pin the knight if the d7-pawn moves. Our simplest defense is to force the bishop to retreat. }
3... a6 { White can maintain control of the a4-e8 diagonal or exchange on c6. }
4. Ba4
{ White saves the bishop and maintains pressure on the c6-knight. Black should simply continue to develop. }
4... Nf6
{ Let's develop a piece and attack the e4-pawn. Just like last turn, White doesn't really threaten to win the e5-pawn yet. Now White has several option, which each take the game in a different direction. }
5. O-O
{ Historically, this is the main line of the Ruy Lopez. Black has several good options, but we're going to aim for our favorite setup. First, it helps to prevent White from getting any ideas of Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
5... b5 { Forcing the bishop to retreat. } 6. Bb3
{ Now we can develop our f8-bishop to its most active square. } 6... Bc5
{ This is the Archangel Variation of the Ruy Lopez. It's possibly Black's best way of playing for a win. Every piece soon reaches an active square. White has the the ability to build a big center with a quick c2-c3 and d2-d4, but Black's pieces will target those pawns and White won't have an easy life. }
7. c3
{ White prepares d2-d4 to build a strong pawn center. This is virtually the only line in our whole repertoire where we're going to let White control the center like that.   Fortunately, all of Black's pieces are active and we're going to cause White serious headaches trying to keep those center pawns protected. }
7... d6
{ Black prepares to develop the c8-bishop and adds another defender to the e5-pawn. }
8. d4 { White attacks the bishop, but it can comfortably retreat. } 8... Bb6
{ The bishop is well placed on b6, where the c7-pawn can protect it and it eyes the d4-pawn. This is a critical position for the Archangel Variation of the Ruy Lopez. White has several plans, but none of them will cause us too much trouble. Black's goals are generally going to be to caste and then play Bg4 if allowed to pin the f3-knight. If White prevents Bg4 with h2-h3, then the bishop will be well placed on b7, eyeing the e4-pawn. It's important to notice that Black can only rarely capture the e4-pawn going forward because Bd5 will fork both black knights. We don't want to fall into that trap! }
9. a4
{ This is White's most aggressive challenge to Black's setup. The immediate threat is axb5, which would pin the a6-pawn and win material. Black can solve the problem by developing the c8-bishop, but the simplest solution is ...Rb8, just stepping off the a-file entirely. }
9... Rb8
{ Black avoids any pins on the a-file and supports the b5-pawn if the b6-bishop ever moves. }
10. axb5
{ White hopes to win the b5-pawn, but Black will always find an easy way to defend or to gain excellent compensation for a small sacrifice. }
10... axb5 11. Na3
{ There isn't any great way to defend the b5-pawn, but development is more important anyway. }
11... O-O { Black develops quickly and doesn't mind sacrificing the b-pawn. }
12. Nxb5 Bg4
{ This pin puts the white center under massive pressure. If Black captures the knight, White must choose between recapturing with the pawn and weakening the kingside or having insufficient defense of the d4-pawn. }
13. Bc2
{ White protects e4 and avoids potential tactics with Black's rook targeting this bishop on the b-fille. }
13... Bxf3 { No need to wait. Black removes a defender of the d4-pawn. } 14.
gxf3
{ White can keep an extra pawn for the moment, but the king on the half-open g-file isn't happy! }
14... Nh5
{ Black's queen heads to h4 or f6. The knight heads to f4 and if Black can find a way to lift a rook it's likely to lead to a queen mate.   Engines evaluate this position as roughly even, but it's certainly more fun to play with the black pieces! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Spanish Opening"]
[Black "Attacking Potential: Kamsky, G. vs. Svidler, P. World Cup, 2011"]
[Result "*"]

{ This was a key game from the 2011 World Cup. The eventual winner, GM Peter Svidler, knocked out the winner of the previous World Cup, GM Gata Kamsky, with an amazing combination.   This isn't a perfect game, but it nicely demonstrates Black's attacking potential in the Archangel Variation. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Kamsky, chooses the Ruy Lopez, always a popular choice at the top level. }
3... a6
{ Svidler forces the bishop to retreat and heads toward the Archangel. } 4. Ba4
Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This is the Archangel Variation of the Ruy Lopez. It's possibly Black's best way of playing for a win. Every piece soon reaches an active square. White has the the ability to build a big center with a quick c2-c3 and d2-d4, but Black's pieces will target those pawns and White won't have an easy life. }
7. a4
{ Like Sukandar, Kamsky, begins with the flexibly 7. a4, threatening to win material with axb5. }
7... Rb8
{ Svidler avoids any pins on the a-file and keeps the b-pawn well protected. }
8. axb5 { White opens the a-file, but Black can comfortably recapture. } 8...
axb5 9. c3
{ Now Kamsky prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4. We've seen this before. }
9... d6 { Black defends the e5-pawn and prepares to develop. } 10. d4
{ White gains space, but Black can simply retreat and keep pressure on the white center. }
10... Bb6
{ This is the right square for the bishop. It's well defended and eyes d4. }
11. Be3
{ Kamsky combines the Be3 plan and the a4 plan that we've seen in the trainable variations.   Of course all of these moves are perfectly reasonable, but they don't really challenge Black's basic setup. }
11... O-O { Black secures the king.  11...Bg4  is also quite reasonable. } 12.
Nbd2 h6
{ Svidler makes sure that White's knight and bishop can't reach the g5-square.   Developing with  12...Bg4  makes sense on this move as well. }
13. h3
{ A logical move for White. Kamsky secures the center by preventing ...Bg4 and avoiding a pin on the f3-knight.   That makes it more difficult for Black to win the d4-pawn, so Svidler begins to focus on hunting the pawn on e4. }
13... Re8
{ Focusing on the e-file. Notice that the f7-pawn isn't vulnerable because White's knight can't safely reach g5. }
14. Qc2 { White develops and protects e4. } 14... exd4
{ Svidler opens the e-file and unleashes the rook against the e4-pawn.   14...Bb7  This normal-looking move runs into a tatical issue.  15.d5  Unleashing a discovered attack against the b6-bishop.  15...Bxe3  16.dxc6  Bxd2  17.cxb7  The bishop on d2 runs out of squares.  17...Bg5  18.h4  Bf4  19.g3  White wins material and Black's in trouble. }
15. cxd4 Na5
{ Sviler hits on a positionally strong plan, but it runs into a serious tactical issue a couple of moves down the line.   15...Bb7  If Black just completes development then White's hands will be full defending the center pawns.   The game is about even. }
16. Ba2 Bb7
{ White's center can't hold, but Svidler underestimated White's next move. }
17. e5 Nd5
{ Positionally black is doing very well with active minor pieces, but Svidler admitted after the game that he missed White's next move. }
18. Bb1
{ Suddenly, Black can't prevent Qh7+ without losing material. Black's pieces are so active that even this threat isn't a knockout. }
18... g6 { Stopping mate, even if it gives up a pawn. } 19. Bxh6 Nc6
{ Even down a pawn and with an exposed king, Black is in the game. The d4- and e5-pawns are both under fire and Black's bishops are focused on the white kingside. }
20. exd6
{ 20.Ne4  This is a bit more precise for White.  20...Nxd4  21.Nxd4  Bxd4  Black wins back the sacrificed pawn, but it costs the bishop pair. White has a dangerous initiative on the kingside dark squares.  22.Bg5  Black's still in the game, but the position is difficult. }
20... Qxd6
{ Black is very active, but the queen is vulnerable near the center.   20...Nxd4  Modern engines think this is safer, not exposing the queen. It's hard to blame either player for mistakes in this sharp position.  21.Nxd4  Bxd4  Chances are even in this sharp position. }
21. Ne4 { Kamsky centralizes a knight and gains time against the black queen. }
21... Qb4 { Svidler keeps pressure on the d4-pawn. } 22. Ba2
{ Kamsky pins the d5-knight to the f7-pawn.   The knight can't move because then Qxg6+ would lead to a quick mate. }
22... Nxd4 { Black can't defend, but only the counterattack is enough! } 23.
Nf6+
{ An exchange of fireworks! Black can't capture on f6 because of Qxg6+ so White will win material, at least for a moment. }
23... Kh8
{ 23...Nxf6??  24.Qxg6+  Oops.  24...Kh8  25.Qg7  This wasn't what Svidler was interested in. }
24. Nxd4
{ An easy mistake to make. The other knight capture is stronger, but it leads to serious complications that are hard to evaluate in advance.   24.Nxd5  Nxf3+  Kamsky probably wanted to avoid this change, which rips open his kingside.  25.gxf3  Bxd5  26.Bxd5  White wins a piece, but won't be able to keep it.  26...Qh4!  Black hits the h6-pawn and threatens Qg3+, taking advantage of the pin on f2. White has to either allow a perpetual check or give back the piece.  27.Qc3+  Bd4  28.Qxc7  Qxh6  The position is wild, but should eventually end in a draw. }
24... Nxf6
{ Black wins back the piece and unblocks the b7-bishop. The two bishops are going to wreck the white kingside. }
25. Nc6 { This fork looks dangerous, but Black has seen a bit further. } 25...
Qh4
{ Black sacrifices the exchange and begins a powerful attack.   25...Bxc6  26.Qxc6  White's bishop pair and safer king will cause Black serious difficulties. }
26. Nxb8
{ Kamsky wins material, but misses Svidler's amazing reply!   26.Be3  Rxe3!  Black's attack is just too strong!  27.fxe3  Re8∓  Every Black piece joins the attack. }
26... Re2
{ What a sacrifice! The final black piece joins the attack and aims to lure the white queen off of the c-file. You can see why the sacrifice is necesary by examining the immedaite 26...Qg3?   26...Qg3?  Taking advantage of the pin on f2 to threaten mate, but White can defend.  27.Nc6  Blocking mate. black can still sacrifice here, but it's not enough to win.  27...Re2!  28.Qc3  White's queen is perfectly placed to offer a trade, defend c6 and attack f6. Black will be fortunate to hold a draw.  28...Bxf2+  29.Kh1  Qxc3  30.bxc3  Bxc6  Black should be OK, but White is the one pressing, up an exchange. }
27. Qc3
{ 27.Qxe2  Let's see the point of Sviler's brilliant sacrifice!  27...Qg3!  White's two rooks don't matter when there's unstoppable mate on g2.  28.Nc6  All that White can do is slow the checkmate.  28...Bxc6  29.Bd5  Bxd5  30.Qf3  Bxf3  31.Rfe1  Qxg2 }
27... Rxf2
{ Black sets up a discovered check that will win enourmous material! } 28. Nc6
{ Slowing the mate, but not saving White. } 28... Rxf1+
{ White resigns. If  29.Kxf1  then  29...Qf2#  .   If  29.Kh2  then  29...Rxa1  picks up another rook for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Spanish Opening"]
[Black "Creating Kingside Weaknesses: Sukandar, I. vs. Lei, T. Women's Grand Swiss, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's enjoy this crushing game by one of the top women in the world, GM Lei Tingjie. Her opponent in this round of the Women's Grand Swiss tournament from 2021 was IM Irine Sukandar. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5
{ This is playable, but I recommend the more forcing option of  5...b5  before ...Bc5. }
6. Nc3 b5 7. Bb3
{ The Nc3 variation of the Spanish is rare at the top level, but you'll probably see it on occasion. White develops a piece toward the center, so it can't be too bad. }
7... d6 { Black defends e5 and prepares to develop the c8-bishop. } 8. a4
{ White tries to take advantage of the pin on the a-file that she would have if she captures on b5. Black can easily diffuse the situation by developing the c8-bishop and making a pin of her own.   8.Nd5  This is an interesting option, but Black doesn't mind trading a knight and bishop for a rook and two pawns.  8...Nxe4  9.Qe2  Nxf2  Black is OK in this imbalanced position. }
8... Bg4 9. axb5
{ White hopes to win a pawn, but Black develops a powerful attack right out of the opening. }
9... Nd4
{ White can't prevent a capture on f3 to damage her kingside structure. } 10.
d3
{ This is too slow. Now Black has a powerful attack.   10.Bc4  This is the best try for White, defending b5 and possibly retreating to defend the kingside. Even so, Black is doing well.  10...axb5  11.Rxa8  This trade activates the black queen on the long diagonal, but White didn't have anything stronger.  11...Qxa8  12.Bxb5+  Nxb5  13.Nxb5  Careful, Black doesn't want to allow a fork on c7.  13...Qb7  14.Nc3  Nxe4  Black wins back the sacrificed pawn and has a great position. }
10... axb5 { Winning back the sacrificed pawn. } 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Be3
{ White completes development, but now Black can expose the king. } 12... Bxf3
13. gxf3 c6 { The queenside pawns nicely restrict the white minor pieces. } 14.
Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qa1 { Should black allow a queen trade? } 15... Qc8
{ No way!   The queen heads to h3 to checkmate White's king. } 16. Ne2 Bb6
{ Black doesn't want to trade the strong bishop. } 17. Ng3 g6
{ Very patient play! Black doesn't let the knight to f5. The exposed white king is a long term problem. There's no way for White to use a move or two to solve her problems. Black can slowly build a powerful attack. }
18. Qc1 Qh3 { Joining the attack and not allowing the white queen in to h6. }
19. Qg5 Ke7
{ Gutsy and strong! Lei doesn't mind pinning her own knight. White doesn't have any pieces helping the queen to attack, so there's nothing for Black to worry about. }
20. c3 h6 { White's queen must retreat. } 21. Qd2 Nh5
{ Black would love to exchange on h5 and recapture with the pawn! If the black rook can join the kingside attack, it will just be mate. }
22. Ne2 g5
{ Lei just wants to open the g-file. White can't do anything about it. } 23.
Qd1 Rg8
{ White resigns. There's no defense against g5-g4 on the next move, with a quick mate to follow.   What a game! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Spanish Opening"]
[Black "Active Pieces: Durarbayli, V. vs. Vidit, Santosh G. World Cup, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ This is an amazing game from the FIDE World Cup in 2021. 2024 World Championship Candidate, Vidit Gujrathi, wins so smoothly, it's hard to pinpoint where his opponent went wrong. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This is the Archangel Variation of the Ruy Lopez. It's possibly Black's best way of playing for a win. Every piece soon reaches an active square. White has the the ability to build a big center with a quick c2-c3 and d2-d4, but Black's pieces will target those pawns and White won't have an easy life. }
7. a4
{ This isn't the most common move order but it's flexible for White. For the moment GM Durabayli keeps open the options of building a big center, using a fork trick or something else. }
7... Rb8
{ The rook steps off of the a-file so there won't be a pin after axb5. } 8.
Nxe5 { White tries a fork trick. Fortunately, it's not too dangerous here. }
8... Nxe5
{ Black has no choice. Other moves allow White to keep a material advantage. }
9. d4
{ White uses this fork to win back the piece, but it's only enough for equality. }
9... Bxd4
{ This is the best way to return the piece. Black draws the white queen to a vulnerable position in the center. }
10. Qxd4 d6
{ Black saves the knight on e5 and gets ready to grab space with the c-pawn. }
11. Bf4 { Targeting the e5-knight, but Black can fight for the initiative. }
11... c5
{ Chasing the queen and getting ready to restrict the white bishop on b3. } 12.
Qe3 c4
{ White has advanced the a-pawn, so this doesn't win material, but the bishop won't have any safe moves after it retreats to a2. }
13. Ba2 Nh5
{ Now that the a2-bishop is stuck on the queenside, every exchange brings Black toward a better endgame. }
14. Nc3 Nxf4 { Vidit trades off the most active white piece. } 15. Qxf4 O-O
{ The king is well placed here. White is solid, but has to find a way to activate the queenside pieces. }
16. axb5 axb5
{ As long as the bishop is on a2, it's hard for White to activate a rook to use the open file. }
17. Rad1
{ With the a-file blocked, White tries to make use of the d-file and attack the backward d6-pawn. }
17... Be6 { White has no threats yet, so Black completes development. } 18. Bb1
{ If White has enough time, he would play Nc3-e2-d4 and c2-c3. Fortunately, Black gets to make moves too! }
18... b4 19. Ne2 Qb6
{ Black connects the rooks and gets ready to continue advancing pawns on the queenside. }
20. h3
{ This misses a tactical trick.  20.Qd2  is safer, discouraging Black from advancing the c-pawn. }
20... c3
{ Black prevents White from freeing the bishop with c2-c3. This looks like a sacrifice, but Black's next move avoids any material losses. }
21. bxc3 Bc4
{ Black pins the white knight and gains time to win back the pawn on c3. } 22.
Rfe1 Bxe2 23. Rxe2 bxc3
{ The c3-pawn in dangerous and blocks the white c-pawn. The bishop on b1 is just burried there. }
24. Ree1
{ 24.Ba2?  Qa6  Black forks the bishop and rook, so White is unable to activate the bishop. }
24... Ra8
{ Preventing Ba2.   Black's whole plan is to prevent the white bishop from moving and essentially winning with an extra piece. }
25. Qg3 Rfc8 { Developing another piece and protecting c3. } 26. Kh2 Ra3
{ Black slowly improves every piece. There's nothing that White can do. } 27.
Re3 Qb4 { Freeing a black rook from needing to defend c3. } 28. f4
{ Whtie lashes out, but it's too late. } 28... Nc4
{ Attacking a rook and heading to d2 to win the white bishop. } 29. Qg4 Rb8
{ Saving the rook. } 30. Rg3 g6
{ It's never too late to blunder checkmate if you're not careful. } 31. f5
{ White bets everything on a kingside attack, but there just aren't enough pieces involved. Black just goes about winning material. }
31... Nd2 32. Qf4 Qd4
{ From d4 the queen perfectly defends against any kingside threats. } 33. fxg6
hxg6 34. Rg5 Ra1
{ Black can capture the bishop at any moment. The rest is agony for White. }
35. Rd5 Qxe4 36. Qxd6 Raxb1 { Finally winning the piece. } 37. Rd4 Qe6 38. Qc7
Qb6 { Black just has a whole extra knight. White resigned. } *

