1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { This move brings us to the Scotch Game. } 3... exd4
4. Bc4
{ This developing move marks the Scotch Gambit.   White delays capturing on d4 and aims for a quick attack. Now  4...Bc5  could allow some very tricky attacking ideas, so we'll play ...Nf6 and castle as quickly as possible. }
4... Nf6 { Black develops and prepares to capture another center pawn. } 5. O-O
{ White sacrifices another pawn. Black should capture it and then return it later on to reach a safe position. }
5... Nxe4 { Eliminating the white pawn center. } 6. Re1
{ This pin looks dangerous, but Black can easily defend the knight. } 6... d5
{ Defending the knight and attacking the white bishop. } 7. Bxd5
{ White's only way to survive is to sacrifice the bishop. } 7... Qxd5
{ Black is ahead by a piece and a pawn. We won't be able to keep it, but White will need to spend time winning back the material. }
8. Nc3
{ Our knight and the d-pawn are both pinned, but we can just move the queen. }
8... Qh5
{ There are plenty of good queen moves, but this one is nice, keeping an eye on the white kingside. }
9. Nxe4 Be6 { Black blocks the e-file and prepares to castle queenside. } 10.
Bg5 { This is a tricky move, trying to keep Black's king in the center. } 10...
Bd6
{ Black is ahead by a pawn, so accepting doubled d-pawns in order to finish development isn't much of a problem. }
11. Nxd6+ cxd6
{ Black is still ahead by a pawn and can't recapture on d4 right now because the white bishop needs defending. }
12. Bf4 { White saves the bishop and aims to win the d-pawns. } 12... Qd5
{ Black defends the pawns and gets ready to castle. White should eventually be able to win back one of the pawns and equalize, but that's a good opening outcome for the black side. }
