[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Scotch Game"]
[Black "Scotch Gambit: 4.Bc4 / 5.e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { This move brings us to the Scotch Game. } 3... exd4
4. Bc4
{ This developing move marks the Scotch Gambit.   White delays capturing on d4 and aims for a quick attack. Now  4...Bc5  could allow some very tricky attacking ideas, so we'll play ...Nf6 and castle as quickly as possible. }
4... Nf6 { Black develops and prepares to capture another center pawn. } 5. e5
{ White chases the f6-knight, but fortunately, we don't have to move it right away. }
5... d5
{ Black gains time on the white bishop.   6.Bb5  is the only move that even gives White even chances. }
6. Bb5
{ White saves the bishop and pins the c6-knight. Now most players try 6... Ne4 here, but let's try a move that's equally good, but more likely to confuse your opponent. }
6... Nd7
{ Black saves the knight, breaks the pin and begins to build pressure against the e5-pawn. }
7. Bxc6
{ This is the most direct way for White to win back the sacrificed pawn, but Black is already better. }
7... bxc6 8. Nxd4
{ This feels natural, threatening the c6-pawn, but Black regains the extra pawn. }
8... Nxe5 9. O-O
{ Black just needs to be careful about threats along the e-file, so it makes sense to develop and protect the knight. }
9... Bd6 10. f4
{ This exposes the white king, but otherwise, black would simply keep an extra pawn. }
10... Ng4
{ Black attacks the h2-pawn and aims for checks on the g1-a7 diagonal if the d4-knight ever moves. }
11. h3
{ Now Black can retreat the knight and keep the safer king or go for an attack with a fishing pole tactic. Either choice is enough for an advantage. }
11... Nf6
{ Blck is ready to castle and has a great game. Remember, When White wins back the c6-pawn, it only equalizes material. }
