[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Scotch Game"]
[Black "Scotch: Potter Variation - 5.Nb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { This move brings us to the Scotch Game. } 3... exd4
4. Nxd4
{ White aims to take over the center, but we can always target the vulnerable d4-knight.   4.c3  This move introduces the Goring Gambit. It's a close relative of the more popular Danish Gambit, so we will cover it there in the Odds and Ends chapter. }
4... Bc5
{ There's no reason to avoid our favorite setup with the bishop coming to c5. We gain a tempo on the knight and start eyeing the f2-pawn. }
5. Nb3
{ This is the Potter Variation. White forces Black's bishop to retreat and often aims to sharp positions with opposite side castling. Fortuantely, Black can equalize with smooth development. }
5... Bb6
{ The best square for our bishop. There's no reason to abandon this strong diagonal. }
6. Nc3 Nf6 { There's no reason not to put our pieces on their best squares. }
7. Qe2
{ White preapres to castle queenside, but Black can caslte first and start quick counterplay. }
7... O-O 8. Be3
{ This is also playable for White, but Black can strike in the center right away. }
8... d5 { A principled move, fighting for the center. } 9. O-O-O
{ White pins the d-pawn, but Black keeps the initiative. } 9... d4
{ The pin on the d-file means that White doesn't lose a piece, but Black has active pieces and good chances to start an attack. }
10. Bg5 a5
{ Black's attack comes quickly, as a5-a4 will gain a tempo on the b3-knight. White is strugling to equalize in this sharp position. }
*

