1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { This move brings us to the Scotch Game. } 3... exd4
4. Nxd4
{ White aims to take over the center, but we can always target the vulnerable d4-knight.   4.c3  This move introduces the Goring Gambit. It's a close relative of the more popular Danish Gambit, so we will cover it there in the Odds and Ends chapter. }
4... Bc5
{ There's no reason to avoid our favorite setup with the bishop coming to c5. We gain a tempo on the knight and start eyeing the f2-pawn. }
5. Nxc6
{ This capture shouldn't cause us too much trouble. It's just important to know the next in-between move. }
5... Qf6
{ Black threatens mate on f2 and avoids a trade of queens if the d-file opens.   5...dxc6  6.Qxd8+  White would have good chances in the endgame.  5…bxc6  is playable, but it’s stronger to develop the queen first, and threatening checkmate is a nice bonus. }
6. Qf3
{ White stops mate, but now either capture on d6, with or without the trade of queens should be fine for Black. }
6... bxc6 { Why not capture toward the center? } 7. Nc3 Qxf3
{ There's nothing to fear in the endgame.   Black went on to win in Nevednichy,V @@StartBracket@@2546@@EndBracket@@-Shirov,A @@StartBracket@@2662@@EndBracket@@ Chess. com INT 2020. }
