[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Scotch Game"]
[Black "Central Activity: Ruano M., Javier vs. Shirov, A., Spanish Rapid Ch., 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's check out a beautiful game by the great GM Alexei Shirov! } 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4
{ White aims to take over the center, but we can always target the vulnerable d4-knight.   4.c3  This move introduces the Goring Gambit. It's a close relative of the more popular Danish Gambit, so we will cover it there in the Odds and Ends chapter. }
4... Qf6
{ Note Shirov's move order features ...Qf6 before ...Bc5.   It's playable, but there's no need for this extravagance. Anyway, the game soon transposes back into our main lines. }
5. Be3 { White defends d4. } 5... Bc5 { And we're back into our main lines. }
6. c3 Nge7 { Shirov keeps developing. } 7. Bc4 b6 8. O-O
{ Now our main recommendation is the safe  8...O-O  but it's no surprise that an attacking player like Shirov prefers 8...Bb7 to prepare castling queenside. }
8... Bb7 9. f3
{ White builds a pawn chain to restrict the b7-bishop.   9.Nb3  This is White's sharpest response to the 8... Bb7 variation.  9...Ne5   9...Bxe3  10.fxe3  This is playable, but the discovered attack along the f-file costs Black a pawn.  10.Nxc5  bxc5  11.Bb3  Bxe4  White has the safer king and a small edge, but both sides have chances in this sharp position. }
9... O-O-O
{ Castling kingside is good too, but not in Shirov's style. Queenside castling, lining a rook up with the white queen is more double-edged. }
10. Nc2
{ This is a little too quiet. White would be better off fighting for the initiative.   10.b4  Instead of retreating, White should try to open lines to the black king. Black has no issues, but at least White has some of his own plans here.  10...Nxd4  11.bxc5  Ne6 }
10... d5
{ This thematic break in the center helps Black activate every piece. } 11.
Bxc5
{ 11.exd5  White won't be able to hold on to this extra pawn.  11...Bxe3+  12.Nxe3  Na5  Black is ready to capture on c4 and then d5, with a great position. }
11... dxc4
{ Capturing the other bishop is good too, but Shirov probably liked keeping the pawn structure in front of his king intact. }
12. Bxe7
{ White refuses to lose time with the bishop, but Black is still ahead in development.   12.Bd4  This makes sense, but Black doesn't fear the trade on d4.  12...Nxd4  13.cxd4  White's center looks impressive, but his development isn't good enough to hold it together.  13...Nc6  14.d5  If White had time to play Nb1-c3-e2 and then defend the d-pawn, he would be doing well, but Black strikes first and wins a pawn.  14...Qxb2  White doesn't have enough compensation for the lost pawn. }
12... Qxe7 { Black frees the f7-pawn to break apart the white pawn chain. } 13.
Qe2 { Saving the queen from the black rook, but now the e4-pawn is pinned. }
13... f5 { Shirov refuses to give White any time to develop peacefully. } 14.
Nd2 Rhe8 { Every black piece is foused on the center of the board! } 15. Rfe1
{ White defends the e-pawn, but the rook will soon be vulnerable on e1. } 15...
Ne5 { Clearing a path for the b7-bisop and heading toward d3. } 16. Nxc4
{ If you're going to get attacked anyway, you might as well win a pawn for your troubles. }
16... Nd3 { Black forks d3 and b2, while also clearing the e-file. } 17. Red1
fxe4
{ Winning back the sacrificed pawn and increasing the strength of the b7-bishop. }
18. Nd4 Nf4 { The start of a devastating combination. } 19. Qe3 Nxg2
{ This isn't the only winning move, but you have to appreciate Shirov's style. }
20. Kxg2 exf3+ { White must give back the extra piece. } 21. Nxf3
{ 21.Kf2  Qh4+  Black wins the queen. } 21... Qxe3
{ Black wins back the knight. After a series of forced exchanges, Black will emerge with an extra pawn and a winning ending. }
22. Nxe3 Rxe3 23. Rxd8+ Kxd8 24. Rf1
{ Black has an extra pawn and White's knight is pinned. The ending is an easy win. }
24... Ke7 25. Kg3 Rxf3+ 26. Rxf3 Bxf3 27. Kxf3
{ For a player of Shirov's technique this is trivial. White could resign here, but he plays a few more moves. }
27... Kf6 28. Kf4 g5+ 29. Kg4 Kg6
{ White resigns. Black would soon make a passed pawn on the kingside and use it to distract the white king, while the black king captures all of White's queenside pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Scotch Game"]
[Black "Opposite Castling: Barbosa, E. A. vs. Quesada Perez, Y. Mercosur Cup, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Let's examine a game between GMs Evandro Barbosa and Yuniesky Quesada Perez. They'll follow the first nine moves of our Potter Variation recommendations before the game begins to get really spicy. }
1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4
{ White aims to take over the center, but we can always target the vulnerable d4-knight.   4.c3  This move introduces the Goring Gambit. It's a close relative of the more popular Danish Gambit, so we will cover it there in the Odds and Ends chapter. }
4... Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Qe2 O-O 8. Bg5 Nd4 9. Qd2 Nxb3
{ Since White is hoping to castle queenside, it's useful to force your opponent to accept doubled pawns on that side of the board. }
10. axb3
{ So far GM Quesada Perez has followed our recommendations against the Potter Variation of the Scotch.   I prefer  10...h6  ,  although his  10...Re8  is also playable. }
10... Re8
{ White's aggressive h4 idea doesn't work well while the white king is still in the center.   11.h4  hxg5  12.hxg5  Ng4  Black has a great position. White doesn't have a good way to defend f2. }
11. O-O-O
{ Despite the half-open a-file, the white king is relatively safe here. } 11...
h6
{ Black tries to break the pin and win the e4-pawn, but White has a nasty surprise in mind. }
12. h4
{ White sacrifices a piece to open a path to the black king. It's too dangerous to accept the offering.   12.Bf4?  Nxe4  Black wins a pawn and keeps a good position.   12.Bh4?  Nxe4!  This is a good trick to remember. Black wins a pawn.  13.Bxd8  Nxd2  14.Rxd2  Rxd8  Black has a great position. }
12... c6
{ A good choice! Black ignores the bait on g5, prevents Nd5 from White and prepares to break open the center with a well-timed d7-d5.   12...hxg5?  This is too greedy.  13.hxg5  White opens the h-file and attacks the knight.  13...Nxe4  14.Nxe4  Rxe4  15.Bd3  White gains another tempo and connects the rooks.  15...Re8  16.Rh7  Rdh1 comes next and Black will have to give up material to avoid a quick checkmate. }
13. Bc4
{ White wants to prevent d7-d5, but now it's going to come more forcefully than ever when Black plays it and attacks the bishop. }
13... d6
{ This is reasonable, but it misses a more direct idea.   13...d5!  The immediate d5 is actually playable!  14.exd5  Bg4  Black can develop and attack the d1-rook. Remember, the bishop is still in danger on g5 as well.  15.Rde1  White doesn't want to block with the f-pawn because Black will get ideas of Be3 to pin the White queen. The downside of this rook move is that Black can trade rooks and then capture the bishop on g5.  15...Rxe1+  16.Qxe1  hxg5  The position remains very sharp, but White needs to find a way to justify the piece sacrifice. }
14. f3
{ This is an innocent-looking move to support the center, but GM Quesada Perez immediately spots that the e3-square is vulnerable and gets a brilliant idea.   14.Bxh6!?  I prefer this sacrifice. There's not a clear win, but the exposed king offers good practical chances for White.  14...gxh6  15.Qxh6 }
14... d5
{ White can't capture on d5 because of a pin coming on the c1-h6 diagonal.   It's amazing how quickly White's position collapses. }
15. Bxf6
{ White hopes that this trade will ease the pressure on the e4-pawn.   15.exd5??  hxg5  Black wins a piece and White can't even recapture because Be3 will win the white queen.  16.hxg5  Be3  Black wins the queen and the game. }
15... Qxf6
{ Black recaptures and develops. White's e-pawn is still pinned as White can't allow Be3. }
16. Bd3
{ White holds things together for now, but Black has the bishop pair and the initiative with kings castled on opposite sides. }
16... d4 { Forcing the knight back. } 17. Ne2 a5
{ White has doubled b-pawns, so there's no way to keep the a-file closed once this pawn advances. }
18. Qf4 Qe7
{ Quesada Perez would like to keep queens on, thank you. Black's attack will arrive before White gets close to the black king. }
19. Bc4 a4
{ Black doesn't need to defend the d-pawn. The open a-file is more important. }
20. Nxd4 axb3 21. Nxb3
{ The knight defends the a1-square, but that barely slows the black attack. }
21... Ra4
{ Black forces White's bishop off of the a2-g8 diagonal. That allows the c8-bishop to reach e6, then the e8-rook can reach the a-file.   All of Black's pieces soon start to eye the white king. }
22. Bd3 Be6 { Black is fully developed and White's attack hasn't started yet. }
23. g4 { Better late than never? } 23... Rea8
{ Black plans Qb4 and then mate with the rooks on a1. } 24. Kd2
{ White desperately tries to run with the king. } 24... c5
{ ...c5-c4 would fork White's knight and bishop. } 25. Bb5 Rb4
{ Hitting b5 and b3. White's position collapses. } 26. Ra1 { A desperate try. }
26... Rd8+ { Black wins a piece. White resigns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Four Knights Game"]
[Black "Scotch Four Knights: Belgrade Gambit (5.Nd5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symmetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5
{ This is the Belgrade Gambit. It's an attempt to make the Scotch Four Knights complicated, but Black has several paths to a good game. }
5... Be7
{ This is the simplest path to an easy position. Black is ready to castle. } 6.
Bf4 d6 { Developing and avoiding any issues on c7. } 7. Nxd4
{ White wins the pawn back. Black can castle now, but there's nothing wrong with trading knights and avoiding any doubled pawns. }
7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nxd5 9. exd5
{ White opens the e-file, but out king won't stay on it for long.   9.Qxd5  O-O  The queen is vulnerable on d5. It most likely has to retreat to d2 in the next few moves. }
9... O-O
{ Most likely White will castle queenside, leading to a sharp game, but one where Black has no problems. We will quickly bring our bishops to the a1-h8 and b1-h7 diagonals and start a quick attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Four Knights Game"]
[Black "Scotch Four Knights: 6.Nxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symmetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. d4
{ This move starts the Scotch Four Knights. It's a popular attempt at all levels for White to keep the game simple and press for a minute advantage. }
4... exd4
{ Black shouldn't try the passive defense with  4...d7-d6  ,  so trading pawns on d4 is the only choice. }
5. Nxd4
{ White recaptures. Now, the most common move is Bb4 to pin the c3-knight. However, our standard setup with ...Bc5 is a good option in this position too! }
5... Bc5
{ There's no need to avoid our favorite setup. We attack the knight on d4 and prepare threats against f2 in the long run. }
6. Nxc6
{ This is a reasonable capture, although it's much less popular than  6.Be3  .   6.Nb3  This transposes to thePotter Variation of the Scotch. }
6... bxc6
{ We don't want to trade queens on d8, so let's capture toward the center. } 7.
Bd3
{ White develops and firmly defends the e4-pawn.   Let's get our king safe. }
7... O-O
{ Black gets the king safe and we're ready to pin the e4-pawn with our rook. }
8. O-O Re8
{ Even when it's not a pin, it's useful to target the white e-pawn and prevent it from safely advancing. }
9. Bg5
{ White can pin the knight, but this isn't a big worry. The first step is to attack the bishop, which gives us the option of eventually playing ...g7-g5 later if we need to. }
9... h6 { Forcing White's bishop to retreat. } 10. Bh4
{ White can maintain the pin, but the bishop has a bit less room to move on the e1-h4 diagonal than it had on the longer c1-h6 line. }
10... Rb8
{ Let's take advantage of the half-open file and develop our rook with a threat. }
11. Rb1
{ White defends. Now Black has a pleasant choice between opening the position and sparking complications or breaking the pin on the f6-knight and playing a balanced game. }
11... Be7
{ This is the calm move. Black is ready to play ...d6 or ...d5 soon with a very safe position. }
*

