[Round "?"]
[White "4) Four Knights Game"]
[Black "Scotch Four Knights: 6.Be3 / 7.Qd2 Mainline #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symmetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. d4
{ This move starts the Scotch Four Knights. It's a popular attempt at all levels for White to keep the game simple and press for a minute advantage. }
4... exd4
{ Black shouldn't try the passive defense with  4...d7-d6  ,  so trading pawns on d4 is the only choice. }
5. Nxd4
{ White recaptures. Now, the most common move is Bb4 to pin the c3-knight. However, our standard setup with ...Bc5 is a good option in this position too! }
5... Bc5
{ There's no need to avoid our favorite setup. We attack the knight on d4 and prepare threats against f2 in the long run. }
6. Be3
{ White develops, protects the knight on d4 and creates a serious threat. Black needs to remember the next move. }
6... Bb6
{ White threatened to capture on c6 and then win the bishop on c5, so we retreat the bishop to a defended square. }
7. Qd2 { White keeps developing and prepares to castle queenside. } 7... O-O
{ Let's get the king safe. } 8. O-O-O
{ White castles queenside and aims for an attack. This is the critical test of our setup, but Black's attacking chances are as good as White's. }
8... Re8 { Let's develop and attack the e4-pawn. } 9. f3
{ White defends the e4-pawn, but must watch out for tactics against the poorly defended e3-bishop. }
9... d5
{ Black should strike in the center now that the e3-bishop is only defended by White's queen. }
10. exd5 { Whie opens the center, but Black is ready. } 10... Nxd5
{ Black recaptures and attacks the e3-bishop. } 11. Nxc6
{ This starts a series of trades, leading to a safe ending. } 11... bxc6
{ Black wins back the piece and protects the knight on d5. } 12. Nxd5
{ White wins a pawn, but only for a move. } 12... cxd5
{ We won't be able to keep the queens on for long, but capturing with the pawn at least gives Black chances to go astray. }
13. Bxb6
{ Black is happy to open lines on the queenside, but White can't afford to keep the bishop hanging on e3. }
13... axb6 { Let's clear a path to win the a2-pawn. } 14. Qxd5
{ White can't be too ambitious with the a-file open. Unfortunately, the fork of our queen and the a8-rook mean we need to enter an endgame. }
14... Qxd5
{ After this trade, the game begins to calm down. White captures on d5 and Black captures on a2, with or without the initial Be6. The endgame is balanced. }
