[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Four Knights Game"]
[Black "Four Knights: 4.Bc4 Mistake #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symmetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. Bc4
{ This bishop move is a famous mistake. Black can of course play 4... Bc5 to transpose to the Canal Variation of the Italian, but there's a surprising move that's even stronger. }
4... Nxe4
{ The infmaous fork trick! Black sacrifices a knight, but soon wins it back with good control of the center. White is already on the back foot. }
5. Bxf7+
{ This is a common mistake. Black's big center and bishop pair are bigger factors than the slightly exposed king. }
5... Kxf7 { Black needs to take the bishop. } 6. Nxe4
{ White wins back the piece, but Black can totally conquer the center. } 6...
d5 7. Neg5+
{ If you find a good way out of check, White will be in serious trouble. } 7...
Kg8
{ This is really all you need to know. Black already threatens e4 to win one of White's knights. White has a terrible position and Black's not being able to castle isn't close to sufficient compensation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Four Knights Game"]
[Black "Four Knights: 4.Bc4 Mistake #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symmetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. Bc4
{ This bishop move is a famous mistake. Black can of course play 4... Bc5 to transpose to the Canal Variation of the Italian, but there's a surprising move that's even stronger. }
4... Nxe4
{ The infmaous fork trick! Black sacrifices a knight, but soon wins it back with good control of the center. White is already on the back foot. }
5. O-O
{ This is an old and tricky gambit, but objectively Black is already much better. }
5... Nxc3 { Let's keep the extra pawn. } 6. dxc3
{ White hopes that the lead in development and pressure on f7 will lead to a strong attack. Fortunately, Black's surprising next move takes much of the force out of White's attack. }
6... f6
{ This is a rare instance where moving the f-pawn early makes sense. Black secures e5 and prevents a white piece from reaching g5. }
7. Nh4
{ White is already reduced to one move threats. Black must prevent Qh5+. } 7...
g6 { Black stops a check on the h5 - e8 diagonal. } 8. f4
{ If we aren't careful, White will break open the center and kingside and Black will run into serious trouble.   Fortunately, Black can use a couple of tactical tricks to grab the initiative. }
8... f5
{ Black uses a discovered attack to target the white knight. Neither  9.g3  or  9.Nf3  are attractive for White but as we will see, the tactical solutions simply don't work. }
9. Qd5 { White threatens mate, but Black just wins a piece. } 9... Qxh4
{ White doesn't have any threats! } 10. Qf7+ Kd8
{ Black steps out of the check and White has no compensation for the missing knight. }
*

