[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symmetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. g3
{ This is the rarely played Glek System.   White will fianchetto and then likely expand on the kingside. There's no reason for us to avoid our typical development scheme. }
4... Bc5 { Black gets ready to castle and targets the f2-pawn. } 5. Bg2 d6
{ This avoids any sort of fork tricks and gets ready to develop another piece. }
6. d3 { White keeps developing. } 6... a6
{ It's useful to give the bishop an escape square so that White can't win the bishop pair with Na4.   Now White has two main plans. One involves an early Be3 and exchanging to open the f-file. The other involves an h3, Kh2, a knight move and kingside expansion with f2-f4.   Neither plan should be too dangerous. }
7. O-O O-O
{ This is the most natural option. The king is comfortable on the kingside. }
8. h3
{ White makes room for the king, with the idea of unpinning the f2-pawn and advancing on the kingside. }
8... h6
{ Black will soon break in the center with ...d6-d5, but it helps to first prevent White's knight and bishop from reaching the g5-square. }
9. Kh2 { White continues the kingside plan, but we can just keep developing. }
9... Be6
{ Black develops the last minor piece and is ready to meet White's kingside plan with counterplay in the center. }
10. Nh4 { White prepares f2-f4, but Black's pawn break comes first. } 10... d5
{ Black has well centralized pieces and great central control. White is the one who will have to work hard not get into trouble out of the opening. }
