[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symmetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. Bb5
{ This move indicates that the game will be a Spanish Four Knights. The main moves for Black are copying with 4...Bb4 or the gambit option, 4...Nd4. However, we can stick to our main ideas and play the slightly unusual 4...Bc5. }
4... Bc5
{ This isn't the most common because some people are afraid of fork trick tactics with Nxe5. Fortunately, it doesn't cause Black too much trouble. }
5. Nxe5
{ White tries to immediately punish Bc5 with a fork trick, but we can 'fall for it.' }
5... Nxe5 { First we take the piece.... } 6. d4
{ White wins back the piece, but we won't make it convenient. } 6... a6
{ Before saving the piece, it's helpful to force the b5-bishop to a worse square. }
7. Be2 { White saves the bishop, but it's not very active on e2. } 7... Bd6
{ Black saves the bishop and protects the knight. } 8. f4
{ White hopes to capture on e5 and and fork two more black pieces. } 8... Nc6
{ We won't be able to keep an extra piece forever, but we can make it inconvenient for White to win it back. }
9. e5 { White forks, but we can find a good use for the bishop. } 9... Bb4
{ Saving the bishop and pinning the c3-knight. } 10. exf6 Qxf6
{ White has won back the piece, but the d4-pawn is vulnerable and the advance of the f-pawn has only created weaknesses. }
11. Be3 d5
{ Black has a comfortable position and went on to win in Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2638@@EndBracket@@ -Eljanov,P @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ Kocaeli 2014. }
