[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Four Knights Game"]
[Black "Navigating Tactics: Wei, Y. vs. Eljanov, P. TUR League, 2014"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's check out a battle between two strong grandmasters in one of our main lines.   GM Wei Yi recently won the Tata Steel chess tournament. GM Pavel Eljanov, with the black pieces has spent decades among the best in the world, representing Ukraine. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symmetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. Bb5 Bc5 5. Nxe5
{ White tries to immediately punish Bc5 with a fork trick, but we can 'fall for it.' }
5... Nxe5 { Black can't let White get away with capturing the pawn. } 6. d4
{ This fork looks like a problem, but the key next move lets Black fight for at least an equal share of the initiative. }
6... a6 { Forcing the bishop to retreat. } 7. Be2 Bd6
{ This is the best way to give back the extra piece. } 8. f4
{ White hopes to build a powerful center and get the piece back as well. } 8...
Nc6 { Black can't let White capture on e5 and fork the knight and bishop. } 9.
e5 { Renewing the fork. } 9... Bb4
{ Eljanov saves the bishop and pins White's knight. White is running out of chances to win back the piece. }
10. exf6
{ 10.d5  White can delay the capture for one more move, but Black doesn't mind.  10...Nxd5  Giving back the piece to break apart White's center.  11.Qxd5  d6  Black already has an easy game. }
10... Qxf6
{ Material is even and Black's already doing well. The f2-f4 advance only weakens the white kingside. }
11. Be3 { White protects d4, but the bishops can be vulnerable on the e-file. }
11... d5
{ Black has equal control of the center and is ready to develop the c8-bishop. }
12. O-O Bxc3
{ Now that there's no pin, Black gives White doubled pawns. The e3-bishop is severly restricted by White's own pawns. }
13. bxc3 Bf5 { Black can still comfortably castle on either side. } 14. c4
{ Top GMs don't go down without a fight. Wei Yi aims to open the position to clear lines for the bishop pair. }
14... O-O-O
{ The king isn't 100% comfortable on the queenside, but it's useful to head the opposite direction of the white king so that Black can safely attack on the kingside. }
15. c3 Qe6 { Black forks the e3-bishop and the c4-pawn. } 16. Bf2 dxc4
{ Winning a pawn and clearing d5 as a useful square for Black's pieces. } 17.
Re1
{ If White has time for Bf3, then it's easy to imagine Black's king coming under attack. Eljanov acts first. }
17... Be4
{ Black focuses on the g2-pawn. White isn't able to control the long diagonal in time. }
18. Qa4
{ White aims to win back the pawn on c4, but this leaves the kingside a little bare.   18.Bf3  This isn't an effective pin.  18...Bxf3!  Black escapes the pin by attacking the white queen.  19.Qxf3  Qd5  Black would love to exchange into an endgame up a pawn. In addition the black knight will dominate White's bishop, which bumps into its own pawns on the dark squares. }
18... Qg6 { Threatening mate on g2 and escaping the e-file pin. } 19. g3
{ White stops mate, but the f2-bishop is miserable and the g-pawn is still vulnerable. }
19... Ne7 { Black swings the knight to the kingside. } 20. Bxc4 Nd5
{ This isn't the engine's preference, but Black keeps firm control of the position and can safely press for a win with little risk.   20...b5  It's hard to blame Eljanov for passing on this engine recommendation. Black's king is open, but there's no way for White to take advantage.  21.Qa3  Hitting the black knight.  21...bxc4  22.Qxe7  f5  Both kings are exposed, but Black has the stronger attack by invading on the kingside light squares. }
21. Bxd5 Rxd5
{ The safer king and more active bishop give Black the better game. } 22. Qd1
Re8 { Activating the final piece. } 23. c4 Rh5
{ The kingside attack looks dangerous and White lashes out. } 24. g4
{ White hopes that cleaing g3 for the bishop will solve his problems, but it doesn't quite work here.   24.Re3  This is safer, but Black still has a dangerous attack.  24...Rh3  Black's h-pawn joins the attack next and Whtie has a difficult defensive task. }
24... Rh3
{ White hopes has that the rook will get trapped here, but there's no time. As long is it's safe, the rook on h3 is a strong attacking piece. }
25. Bg3 h5 { Ripping open a path to the white king. Black should be winning. }
26. f5 Qg5 { Saving the queen and preparing ...hxg4. } 27. Qc1
{ White wants to exchange queens, but Black avoids it for the moment. } 27...
Qxg4 { The first pawn falls. } 28. Qf4 Qxf4 29. Bxf4 Rh4
{ White resigned. Black will soon win at least one more pawn on f5 or d4.   White could keep fighting for a while, but the result at the top level isn't really in doubt. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Four Knights Game"]
[Black "Creating Weaknesses: Engqvist, T. vs. Amin, B., EU Cup, 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's check out a Scotch Four Knights between IM Thomas Engqvist and GM Bassem Amin. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White simply develops and protects e4.   For the moment, there's nothing better to do than keep things symmetrical, but we will make it spicy in just a moment. }
3... Nf6
{ This enters the Four Knights Game.   Now White has a major choice between the Scotch Four Knights and The Spanish Four Knights. Basically, these are versions of more popular openings with all of the knights developed. White also has a couple of more minor options that won't cause us any trouble. }
4. d4
{ With the Scotch Four Knights White hopes for a tiny advantage with no risk. You'll see that GM Amin has no intention of allowing his opponent an easy game. }
4... exd4
{ Black shouldn't try the passive defense with  4...d7-d6  ,  so trading pawns on d4 is the only choice. }
5. Nxd4
{ White recaptures. Now, the most common move is Bb4 to pin the c3-knight. However, our standard setup with ...Bc5 is a good option in this position too! }
5... Bc5
{ Amin chooses our favorite Bc5 setup. Bb4 is much more common, so his opponent may have been a bit surprised already. }
6. Be3
{ White protects the knight and threatens to win a piece with Nxc6 followed by Bxc5.   6.Nxc6  This is the other main move, which is covered in the trainable variations.   Meanwhile,  6.Nb3  transposes into theScotch Game and other knight moves are simply bad for White. }
6... Bb6 { Amin retreats the bishop to a protected square. } 7. Nxc6
{ White aims to damage Black's structure and make a couple of trades, but it doesn't cause any trouble.   7.Qd2  is the main alternative.   You can check out the trainable variations for more coverage. }
7... bxc6 { Amin captures toward the center and avoids a trade of queens. } 8.
Bxb6
{ White exchanges on b6 because a trade on e3 would damage White's kingside pawn structure. }
8... axb6 { Capturing toward the center and opening a path for the a8-rook. }
9. Bd3
{ Simple development.   9.e5  This looks aggressive, but Black wouldn't move the knight.  9...Qe7  Black pins the e-pawn and continues to develop.  10.f4  This is White's most ambitious move, but the e5-pawn remains pinned.   10.Qe2  Nd5  Black has found a strong square for the knight and is alrady playing for advantage out of the opening.  10...d6  White will have a hard time defending the pinned pawn on e5. }
9... O-O
{ Amin gets castled first and then prepares counterplay in the center. } 10.
O-O { White also secures the king. } 10... Re8
{ This is Amin's first move that doesn't coincide with my recommendations. I prefer the immediate d7-d5 pawn break to clarify the center. Amin's move is also reasonable. He brings presure against the e4-pawn and avoids immediate exchanges.   10...d5  Black has absolutely no problems and can meet e4-e5 with any safe knight move to keep a good position. }
11. Qf3 { White connects his rooks and protects e4. } 11... d6
{ Preparing to develop the c8-bishop. ...d7-d5 is also good, but Amin wants to keep more pieces on the board in order to build long term pressure. }
12. Rfe1 Bd7 { Calm play, just protecting the c6-pawn. } 13. h3 Ra5
{ A benefit of the half-open a-file is that Black can develop the rook this way and swing it toward the kingside. }
14. Re3
{ White lifts a rook too. He wants the option of defending the e4-pawn with both rooks. }
14... h6
{ There are many reasonable ideas here and GM Amin chooses a quiet improving move. Basically, he doesn't have to worry about back rank threats and may want to place a piece on g5 at some point and have it be protected there. }
15. Rae1 Rae5
{ The battle revolves around the e4-pawn. Black wants to build up pressure and win it, while White just wants to keep it secure. }
16. a3 b5
{ Black opens a new front. The b5-b4 advance can displace the c3-knight and indirectly weaken the e4-pawn. }
17. Bf1 Qb8
{ Black supports the ...b4 push. The queen will also be strong on the g1-a7 diagonal later on. }
18. Qd1 b4
{ Black opens the queenside and White is definitely on the back foot.   Engqvist lashes out on the kingside to complicate the game. }
19. f4 R5e7
{ This natural - looking move turns out to be a subtle mistake.   19...R5e6!  It turns out that the rook is safest on the sixth rank.  20.axb4  Qxb4  The queen gets active and now b2 and e4 are both under fire.  21.Qf3  d5  Breaking apart White's center.  22.e5  d4  This fork wins material and White's in trouble. }
20. axb4 Qxb4 { The queen is active and targets both the e4- and b2-pawns. }
21. Qf3 { White sacrifices the b2-pawn and sets a trap. } 21... d5
{ Black breaks apart the white center and soon wins. I suspect that both players assumed that Black was winning here. In reality, White has a surprising tactical resource to stay in the game.   21...Qd4  22.Kh2  Nd5  23.R3e2  Nxc3  24.bxc3  Qc5   21...Qxb2?  The queen gets in trouble on the queenside.  22.Rb1  Qa3   22...Qxc2  23.Re2  The queen is trapped!  23.Nd5  White uses a discovered attack on the queen to win an exchange. }
22. exd5
{ White misses the one saving resource and now Black totally takes over.   22.e5!  It looks like d5-d4 should win for Black here, but White has an amazing idea.  22...d4  23.Ne4!!  A shocking sacrifice. This is where we see why Black's rook would be better off on the sixth rank.  23...dxe3  24.Nxf6+  White wins back material and rips open the kingside.  24...Kh8   24...gxf6?!  Now White has a dangerous attack.  25.Qg3+  Kh8  26.exf6  Threatening mate and hitting the e7-rook.  26...Rg8  27.Qh4  Renewing the mate threat.  27...Rg6  28.fxe7  White has a comfortable position.  25.c3!  A useful in-between-move.  25...Qc5  26.Bd3  Amazingly, White can just leave the knight hanging on f6 and build an attack. With perfect play the complications should end in a perpetual check.  26...gxf6  27.Qh5  Black can stop mate, but not escape the checks.  27...f5  28.Qxh6+  Kg8  29.Qg5+  These complications just demonstrate that chess is a difficult game! It's no surprise that White failed to find the several amazing moves to draw this tough position. }
22... Qd4 { Black pins the rook and White's position swiftly collapses. } 23.
Kf2 Bg4 { A beautiful shot. The bishop can't be safely captured. } 24. Qg3
{ This doesn't help for long.   24.hxg4  Rxe3  Black soon wins back the bishop with interest.  25.Rxe3  Rxe3  26.Qxe3  Nxg4+  This fork wins the queen and the game. }
24... Qd2+ { White resigns. Black is about to pick up the rook on e3. } *

