[Black "Bishop's Opening: 2.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. Bc4
{ The Bishop's Opening is perfectly sound, but will nearly always transpose to one of our other openings. }
2... Nc6 { Black develops toward the center. } 3. d3
{ If  3.Nf3  , we transpose to an Italian Game by playing  3...Nf6   And in case of  3.Qh5  , transposing to the Wayward Queen Attack @@StartBracket@@or Scholar's Mate@@EndBracket@@, we simply play  3...g6  . }
3... Nf6
{ At this point, the game will almost always transpose to one of our other openings,  4.Nf3  is an Italian and  4.Nc3  is a Vienna. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "King's Gambit: 2.f4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. f4
{ This is the romantic King's Gambit. White sacrifices a pawn and opens the kingside, but often creates wild complications.   2.Bc4  The Bishop's Opening is perfectly sound, but will nearly always transpose to one of our other openings.  2...Nc6  Black develops toward the center.  3.Qh5  This transposes to the Wayword Queen Attack.   2.Bc4  Nc6  3.d3  Nf6  At this point the game will almost always transpose to one of our other openings.  4.Nf3  is an Italian and  4.Nc3  is a Vienna. }
2... Bc5
{ Let's try to calm the King's Gambit with this safe developing move. It's quite an annoying one for a gambiteer to face. Black refuses to give up the center nad makes it difficult for White to ever castle. }
3. fxe5 { White can hardly ever get away with taking the pawn on e5. } 3...
Qh4+ { Black forks the white king and then e4-pawn. } 4. g3
{ 4.Ke2  instead would already allow  4...Qxe4#  . } 4... Qxe4+
{ Another fork! } 5. Ne2 Qxh1 { Black wins a whole rook! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "King's Gambit: 2.f4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. f4
{ This is the romantic King's Gambit. White sacrifices a pawn and opens the kingside, but often creates wild complications.   2.Bc4  The Bishop's Opening is perfectly sound, but will nearly always transpose to one of our other openings.  2...Nc6  Black develops toward the center.  3.Qh5  This transposes to the Wayword Queen Attack.   2.Bc4  Nc6  3.d3  Nf6  At this point the game will almost always transpose to one of our other openings.  4.Nf3  is an Italian and  4.Nc3  is a Vienna. }
2... Bc5
{ Let's try to calm the King's Gambit with this safe developing move. It's quite an annoying one for a gambiteer to face. Black refuses to give up the center nad makes it difficult for White to ever castle. }
3. Nf3 { White develops and builds pressure on the e5-pawn. } 3... d6
{ Black supports the center and prepares to develop the c8-bishop. } 4. Nc3
{ White just develops toward the center. } 4... Nf6
{ This is a useful developing move. It's nice to bring out the kingside knight before it's queenside counterpart to avoid any Bb5 pins. }
5. Bc4
{ White develops and targets f7, but it doesn't cause any serious threats. }
5... Nc6 { Developing another piece to the center. } 6. d3
{ This transposes to our coverage of the Vienna Game, elsewhere in this chapter. }
*

