1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. f4
{ This is the romantic King's Gambit. White sacrifices a pawn and opens the kingside, but often creates wild complications.   2.Bc4  The Bishop's Opening is perfectly sound, but will nearly always transpose to one of our other openings.  2...Nc6  Black develops toward the center.  3.Qh5  This transposes to the Wayword Queen Attack.   2.Bc4  Nc6  3.d3  Nf6  At this point the game will almost always transpose to one of our other openings.  4.Nf3  is an Italian and  4.Nc3  is a Vienna. }
2... Bc5
{ Let's try to calm the King's Gambit with this safe developing move. It's quite an annoying one for a gambiteer to face. Black refuses to give up the center nad makes it difficult for White to ever castle. }
3. Nf3 { White develops and builds pressure on the e5-pawn. } 3... d6
{ Black supports the center and prepares to develop the c8-bishop. } 4. b4
{ This mixture of the Evans Gambit and King's Gambit is quite rare, but GM Nigel Short loves to play it in blitz, so let's be ready just in case you play him. }
4... Bxb4
{ Retreating the bishop gives White a big space advantage, so let's take the pawn. }
5. c3
{ The bishop must retreat. It's useful to stay on the e1-a5 diagonal to pin the d2 and c3-pawns. }
5... Ba5 6. fxe5
{ White can capture once on e5, but the knight is still stuck preventing a dangerous queen check on h4. }
6... dxe5
{ There's no reason to avoid the recapture on e5. Black remains a pawn ahead. }
7. Na3 { White hopes to trap the black bishop with Nc4. } 7... Bb6
{ There's no reason to wait for Nc4. Let's move the bishop to a safe square in preparation for Nc4. }
8. Nc4 Nc6 { Black keeps developing and protects e5. } 9. Ba3
{ White hopes to prevent Black from castling, but Black has an extra pawn and good central control, so it's not enough for White. }
9... Bg4
{ Black continues to develop and pins the white knight. We are just a couple of moves from completing development and leaving White to wonder what the point of giving up the b-pawn was. }
*

