1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. f4
{ This is the romantic King's Gambit. White sacrifices a pawn and opens the kingside, but often creates wild complications.   2.Bc4  The Bishop's Opening is perfectly sound, but will nearly always transpose to one of our other openings.  2...Nc6  Black develops toward the center.  3.Qh5  This transposes to the Wayword Queen Attack.   2.Bc4  Nc6  3.d3  Nf6  At this point the game will almost always transpose to one of our other openings.  4.Nf3  is an Italian and  4.Nc3  is a Vienna. }
2... Bc5
{ Let's try to calm the King's Gambit with this safe developing move. It's quite an annoying one for a gambiteer to face. Black refuses to give up the center nad makes it difficult for White to ever castle. }
3. Nf3 { White develops and builds pressure on the e5-pawn. } 3... d6
{ Black supports the center and prepares to develop the c8-bishop. } 4. c3
{ This is White's most ambitious try. White plans for d2-d4 to take over the center. On the other hand, he or she will have to defend it against threats from our pieces. }
4... Nf6 { Let's develop and eye the e4-pawn. } 5. d4
{ White forces our bishop to retreat, but that's anothe pawn that must be defended. }
5... exd4
{ It's useful to trade so that we don't need to defend the e5-pawn any longer. }
6. cxd4 { White chases the bishop. } 6... Bb6
{ We don't want to check because White would force a trade of bishops. From b6 the bishop can keep pressure on the d4-pawn. }
7. Nc3 { White defends e4. } 7... O-O
{ Black castles quickly and gets ready to attack on the e-file. } 8. e5
{ This is White's best try. The pawn is relatively secure on e5, prootected by two of its compatriots. }
8... dxe5
{ Black has less space, but the lead in development will cause White a lot of trouble. }
9. fxe5 Re8 { Let's save the knight by developing and pinning the e-pawn. } 10.
Be2 Nc6
{ This powerful novelty offers a fully sound piece sacrifice. Black is going to build an enormous lead in development and start hunting the white king in the center.   10...Nd5  Objectively this is a small mistake, but I understand if you don't want to enter the sacrificial mayhem that we're about to get into in the main line.  11.O-O  Be6  Black will be able to complete development with a decent game. Objectively the white pawn center offers a small advantage, which is why 10...Nc6 is more principled. }
11. exf6 { White grabs a piece, but Black just keeps developing. } 11... Bg4
{ Black prepares a well timed capture on f3, allowing a deadly queen check on h4. }
12. O-O
{ White might try to get the king safe by castling, but it's just entering the line of fire! }
12... Nxd4
{ Clearing the diagonal toward White's king.   13.Nxd4  Black starts a long combination to win back the sacrificed piece.  13...Qxd4+  Hitting White's king and queen.  14.Kh1  The king can hide, but Black still wins material.  14...Bxe2  Winning material.  15.Nxe2  Qxd1  Removing the defender of the white knight.  16.Rxd1  Rxe2  Black wins back the sacrificed piece and maintains an extra pawn. }
13. Kh1 Nxe2 { Black wins back the sacrificed knight. } 14. Nxe2 Qxd1
{ Removing the defender of e2. } 15. Rxd1 Rxe2
{ Black is up material in the endgame. } *

