{ This agressive move looks dangerous, but it would be shocking if White's queen and pawn based attack was dangerous without any minor pieces involved. }
5... Ng4 { Black saves the knight and forks White's queen and e5-pawn. } 6. Qe4
{ White keeps attacking the g4-knight, but Black can sacrifice it for enourmous compensation. }
6... Ngxe5
{ White must aim to win the e5-knight. Otherwise Black is just up a pawn. } 7.
f4 { White breaks more opening principles, but will eventually win a knight. }
7... d5 { Black gains time on the exposed white queen. } 8. Qe2
{ White maintains the pin. } 8... Bb4+ 9. Kd1 f6 10. fxe5 fxe5
{ Black has a dominant position!   Black will soon castle and threatens to win material with ...Nd4 and other powerful ideas. }
