1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. d4
{ The Danish Gambit can lead to fireworks if Black gets greedy, but we aren't going to let White gain a dangerous lead in development. }
2... exd4 3. c3
{ This is the Danish Gambit.   In the modern engine age,  3...Qe7  seems theoretically best, but the positions aren't intuitive to play.   Let's go with a simpler solution to comfortably equalize. }
3... d5
{ Black fights back in the center instead of accepting White's sacrifice. } 4.
exd5 Qxd5
{ Black is happy to develop the queen. The pawn on c3 makes it harder for White's knight to develop to attack the queen. }
5. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black develops toward the center. Note that you can reach this position with aScotch move order as well, when Nf3 and ...Nc6 are played before the d4 advance. }
6. cxd4 Bg4 { Black develops and pins the white knight. } 7. Be2 Bb4+
{ Let's develop another piece and make another pin.   7....Bxf3?  is not terrible by itself but please don't fall into this well-known trap...  8.Bxf3  Qxd4??  Black's queen won't make it out of here.  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  10.Qxd4  Remember this trap and don't rush to capture on d4. }
8. Nc3 Bxf3
{ Remember, we're not doing this to capture on d4, but to lure the white bishop off of the f1-a6 diagonal. }
9. Bxf3 Qc4
{ A great square for the queen! Black prevents White from castling and attacks c3 and d4. }
10. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ Capturing with the queen is playable, but it's better to keep the f1-a6 diagonal under control and keep the white king in the center. }
11. Qe2+
{ White can't castle and doesn't want to lose material on c3 or d4, so there's nothing better than forcing an endgame. }
11... Qxe2+ { Black doesn't have any options but entering the endgame. } 12.
Kxe2 O-O-O
{ Black's king can protect the vulnerable queenside pawns and the rooks will soon control the central files to target White's king and the d4-pawn.   The game is roughly even with best play, but Black has an easier time generating an initiative. }
