1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. Nc3
{ This introduces the Vienna Game. White develops and keeps the f2-pawn unblocked so that it can advance later on. }
2... Nc6
{ We will stick with our favorite developing plan. This prevents any d2-d4 pawn break.   We don't mind allowing the risky f4 advance instead. Now White has a wide set of options. }
3. Bc4
{ This is a logical developing move. We will keep developing along our normal plan and if White ever plays Nf3 then the game will transpose to an Italian Game.   In this chapter we will focus on White's plans with an early f2-f4. }
3... Nf6
{ Developing and getting ready for a fork trick @@StartBracket@@Nxe4@@EndBracket@@ if White develops the g1-knight on the next turn. }
4. d3 { White keeps e4 well protected and prepares f2-f4 as well. } 4... Bc5
{ This is a nice multi-purpose move. Black develops and is ready to transpose to the Canal Variation of the Italian. However, the bishop is also perfectly placed in case of f2-f4, when it will make it difficult for White to castle. }
5. f4
{ With this advance we reach a position that you can also get from the King's Gambit Declined. White has a difficult time castling, but hopes that advancing the pawn to f5 or capturing on e5 could spark a kingside attack. }
5... d6 { Let's defend e5 and prepare to develop the bishop from c8. } 6. Nf3
{ White discourages any future queen checks on h4. Black has many reasonable options here, but we're going to focus on preserving our strong c5-bishop and aim to soon capture the white bishop on c4. }
6... a6
{ This little move ensures that White can't trap our bishop with Na4.   Meanwhile we are now threatening ...Na5 to catch the white bishop. }
7. a3
{ White can preserve the bishop. When that happens, we will develop and make a pin. }
7... Bg4
{ Black prepares to capture on f3 and then to gain time on the white queen. }
8. h3 { White doesn't want to let us maintain the pin. } 8... Bxf3
{ We can't retreat to h5 because g2-g4 would trap the bishop. } 9. Qxf3 Nd4
{ A great square for the knight. Black forks the queen and the c2-pawn. } 10.
Qg3 { White sacrifices the c2-pawn and the a1-rook. It doesn't quite work. }
10... Nxc2+
{ Let's win material!   The game could continue:  11.Kd1  Nxa1  Let's call White's bluff.  12.Qxg7  Rf8  Black keeps everything defended.  13.fxe5  dxe5  We can recapture and open the d-file toward the white king.  14.Bg5  Be7  15.Rf1  White's attack looks scary, but we just need one more key move.  15...b5  White's attack falls apart. The bishop can't move without dropping the d3-pawn. Black should win with best play. }
