{ White discourages any future queen checks on h4. Black has many reasonable options here, but we're going to focus on preserving our strong c5-bishop and aim to soon capture the white bishop on c4. }
6... a6
{ This little move ensures that White can't trap our bishop with Na4.   Meanwhile we are now threatening ...Na5 to catch the white bishop. }
7. a3
{ White can preserve the bishop. When that happens, we will develop and make a pin. }
7... Bg4
{ Black prepares to capture on f3 and then to gain time on the white queen. }
8. h3 { White doesn't want to let us maintain the pin. } 8... Bxf3
{ We can't retreat to h5 because g2-g4 would trap the bishop. } 9. Qxf3 Nd4
{ A great square for the knight. Black forks the queen and the c2-pawn. } 10.
Qd1 O-O
{ Black has the much safer king.   Note that  11.Be3  would lose material to  11...Nxc2+!  . }
