1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. Nc3
{ This introduces the Vienna Game. White develops and keeps the f2-pawn unblocked so that it can advance later on. }
2... Nc6
{ We will stick with our favorite developing plan. This prevents any d2-d4 pawn break.   We don't mind allowing the risky f4 advance instead. Now White has a wide set of options. }
3. g3
{ This somewhat rare development scheme is popular in correspondence chess. We can just follow our plan. }
3... Bc5 { Let's develop and target f2. } 4. Bg2 Nge7
{ 4...Nf6  Our normal development with ...Nf6 is quite reasonable here as well.  Unfortunately, White's plan with Nge2, O-O, h3, Kh2 and f2-f4 is a bit annoying here. That's why we're going to place the knight on e7 and advance our f-pawn first!  Like White, we are going to keep the option of advancing the f-pawn available. Since the white bishop is already committed to g2, we won't have to worry much about tactics on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
5. d3 O-O
{ First we get the king safe, then we clear the f-file so that our rook attacks f2. }
6. Nge2 f5 { Clearing a path to f2 for the rook. } 7. O-O d6
{ This is Black's basic setup in this line. We can choose later between ...f5-f4 or ...fxe4 to allow our pieces to flood the white kingside and create a dangerous attack. }
