1. e4 e5
{ In this chapter we will examine all of White's unusual choices on move two.   None of these are popular at higher levels, but you never know what you will run into in any given game, so it helps to be a bit prepared. You don't need to memorize these lines very deeply, but we will go into some detail, just to make sure you're ready if you know that an opponent plays one of the sharper gambits. }
2. Nc3
{ This introduces the Vienna Game. White develops and keeps the f2-pawn unblocked so that it can advance later on. }
2... Nc6
{ We will stick with our favorite developing plan. This prevents any d2-d4 pawn break.   We don't mind allowing the risky f4 advance instead. Now White has a wide set of options. }
3. f4
{ King's Gambit style! Fortunately for us, it's more fun than it is good. Black can actually just capture the pawn.   3.Nf3  Nf6  transposes to a Four Knights Game. }
3... exf4
{ White doesn't have a simple way to win back the pawn. Meanwhile, ...Qh4+ is a big problem. }
4. Nf3
{ White prevents the check on h4, but we will prove that the knight is vulnerable. }
4... g5
{ This might look strange, but from g5, the pawn defends f4 and prepares to attack the white knight on f3. }
5. h4 { White prepares a tricky, but unsound sacrifice. } 5... g4
{ If the knight must retreat, then Black is doing very well. Most of the time, White aims to sacrifice this knight on f7, but we have a nasty surprise in mind. }
6. Ng5 f3
{ This is a powerful novelty, sure to surprise your opponent. We will soon trap the g5-knight, but first we break the coordination of White's pieces. }
7. Bc4 { This looks dangerous, but we have a good defense. } 7... Ne5
{ Black defends f7 and attacks c4. } 8. Bb3 h6
{ Trapping the knight.   Play could continue:  9.d4  This counterattack almost keeps White in the game, but Black gets a wall of powerful pawns.  9...hxg5  We can capture on g5 and then h4.  10.dxe5  gxh4  These kingside pawns are getting far up the board!  11.gxf3  h3  Getting close to promotion and preparing a powerful queen check on h4.  12.fxg4  Qh4+  13.Kf1  Bc5  Developing and threatening mate. Now White has one trick, but we're a couple of moves from totally taking control of the game.  14.Bxf7+  Don't panic. Let's just capture the piece.  14...Kxf7  15.Qd5+  This fork isn't a problem.  15...Ke8  Let's escape the check and make room for our rook to reach the f-file.  16.Qxc5  Ne7  White has no good defense against Rf8+ and a deadly attack. }
