[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Counteraggression: Zeitlein, M. vs. Marciano, D. Bucharest, 1993"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's see how GM David Marciano handed the black side of the Vienna Game / King's Gambit hybrid against fellow GM Michael Zeitlein. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4
{ King's Gambit style! Fortunately for us, it's more fun than it is good. Black can actually just capture the pawn.   3.Nf3  Nf6  transposes to a Four Knights Game. }
3... exf4 { Black captures the pawn and prepares a queen check on h4. } 4. Nf3
{ White develops and prevents a check. The downside for White is that the knight can be vulnerable. }
4... g5 { Black has no intention of giving back the extra pawn. } 5. d4
{ White builds a big center, but we can still take advantage of the exposed white king. }
5... g4
{ If the knight moves, then ...Qh4+ is a big problem for White, so he chooses to sacrifice. }
6. Bc4 gxf3 { A knight is a knight! } 7. O-O
{ The main variation covered in the trainable variations is7...Qxf3  . GM Zeitlein's move is also interesting.   It's logical to bring the rook to the f-file and hope to secure the king. However, Black has several paths to an advantage. GM Marciano chooses the most spectacular one. }
7... Nxd4
{ A powerful sacrifice, although it's not the only good move.   7...Bg7  This is a less complicated way to keep an advantage. Black develops and targets d4.  8.Qxf3  Bxd4+  Winning a pawn and clearing the e5-square.  9.Kh1  Ne5  Black has a winning material advantage and just wants to trade pieces.  10.Qxf4  Qf6!  Black aims to give up a piece on f6 and then win it back on c4. White has only a small lead in development at this point and it's certainly not enough to compensate for Black's extra knight. }
8. Bxf4
{ White ignores the knight and plays for an initiative.   8.Qxd4?  Black can take advantage of the exposed white king and queen to win material.  8...Qg5!  Threatening both checkmate on g2 and a pin on the g1-a7 diagonal.  9.Rf2  Bc5  Black wins substantial material. }
8... Bc5
{ Black prepares a strong discovered check. White plays a natural response, but misses an opportunity to complicate the game. }
9. Kh1
{ 9.Bxf7+!  This sacrifice wins back a bit of material for White, although Black is still doing well.  9...Kxf7  The king is exposed here, but only for a bit.  10.Be3  Ke8  Black brings the king back to relative safety.  11.Bxd4  Bxd4+  White begins to run out of pieces to fuel the attack.  12.Qxd4  Qf6  Black is happy to trade queens. White doesn't have full compensation for the sacrificed piece. }
9... d6 { White has no immediate threats, so Black just develops. } 10. Be3 Be6
{ A nice counterattack. If White trades on e6 then Nxe6 will escape danger. }
11. Bxd4 fxg2+ { A useful in-between-move to expose the white king. } 12. Kxg2
Bxc4
{ Black doesn't mind giving back some of the extra material to trade into a much better ending. }
13. Bxh8 Bxf1+ 14. Qxf1 Qd7
{ The opening is more-or-less complete. White has won back the sacrificed piece, but Black has an extra pawn and a much safer king. }
15. Qf4 O-O-O
{ If you're wondering who's better in this sharp position, just look at the two kings. Black is quite cozy on the queenside and White's king is hanging out on an open file! }
16. Rf1 Nh6 { Black is happy to trade this knight for the bishop on h8. } 17.
h3 Rxh8 18. Qxh6
{ Black has an extra pawn and the better position. The game won't last long. }
18... Bd4
{ Black may be happy to trade on c3, but also the bishop is effective on the long diagonal. }
19. Qh5 Rg8+ { Causing trouble for the white king. } 20. Kh2 Qe6
{ Eyeing the e4-pawn. } 21. Rf3 Be5+
{ It's useful to push White's king to the corner before capturing on c3. } 22.
Kh1 Bxc3 { Winning the e4-pawn. } 23. bxc3 Qxe4
{ Black wins material and pins the rook on f3. White won't be able to avoid a lost king and pawn endgame. }
24. Qxf7 Rg3
{ Attacking the pinned rook. White can force a trade of queens with Qf5+, but then Black picks up a couple of pawns and wins the rook endgame. }
25. Kh2 { Maybe hoping for  25...Qxf3??  , which would allow checkmate on e8. }
25... Rxf3
{ White resigns.   An impressive display by Black, not giving White many opportunities to recover from the dubious opening. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Odds & Ends"]
[Black "Punishing Unsound Play: Nepomniachtchi, I. vs. Carlsen, M., Leuven Blitz, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4 3. Qxd4
{ This is the Center Game.   A few aggressive players like to try it on occasion, but developing the queen early rarely works out well.   3.Nf3  You can play ...Bc5 if you want to take the game in a new direction, but there's also no reason to avoid 3...Nc6 to transpose directly into the Scotch Game.  3...Nc6  transposes to a Scotch Game. }
3... Nc6 { Carlsen develops and forces the queen to retreat. } 4. Qe3 Bb4+
{ I recommend  4...Nf6  before this bishop move, but Carlsen's move order is also reasonable. }
5. Nc3 { Now the game transposes back into our repertoire. } 5... Nf6
{ Magnus gets ready to castle and attacks the e4-pawn. } 6. Bd2 O-O
{ Black secures the king and prepares to fight for the e-file with the rook. }
7. O-O-O
{ When up against a giant like Magnus, opposite side castling and a sharp game isn't a bad strategy overall. Unfortunately, for White the position is just not very good. }
7... Re8 { Preparing to win the e4-pawn. } 8. Qf4
{ This is a rare choice. White unpins the e-pawn.   8.Qg3  ,  eyeing the g7-pawn is more common. }
8... Bxc3 { Carlsen starts by winning the e4-pawn.   Why not? } 9. Bxc3 Rxe4
{ Black wins the pawn and gains a tempo on the queen. } 10. Qg3
{ White hopes for tactics against the g7-pawn, but there's not much compensation for the sacrificed pawn.   10.Bxf6  Black doesn't mind going into an endgame with an extra pawn.  10...Rxf4  Trading queens works out well for Black.  11.Bxd8  Nxd8  Black is up a pawn, with great winning chances in the endgame. }
10... d5
{ Carlsen defends his rook, controls the center and gets ready to develop the last minor piece. }
11. f3 Re8
{ The rook did its job winning a pawn. It's OK to retreat.   11...Re6  This may be a bit more accurate. The rook can swing to queenside once the c6-knight moves. }
12. Ne2 a5 { Carlsen prepares ...Nb4 to target the white queenside. } 13. Nf4
Nb4
{ Targeting the a2 and c2-pawns. Black would love to exchange on b4 and open the a-file for the a8-rook. }
14. Bxf6
{ This aggressive move is logical, but it allows Black to take over.   14.Bc4  This is a safer move. The d-file pin ensures that Black can't win the bishop right away, but it can't join the attack from the queenside.  14...c6  Securing the d-pawn.  15.Bb3  Bf5  Black has a comfortable advantage. }
14... Qxf6 15. a3
{ If the black knight had to move then White would capture on d5 with a good position, but Carlsen wisely played for an attack instead. }
15... Bf5
{ Black includes every piece in the attack. White's only hope is to grab material and somehow hold on. }
16. axb4 axb4
{ Including the a8-rook in the attack will soon decide the game. } 17. Nxd5
Ra1+ { The white king is forced into the open. } 18. Kd2 Qxb2
{ Black threatens mate on c2. } 19. Qxc7
{ White defends c2, but Black mates quickly.   19.Bd3  This only extends the day for a few moves.  19...Bxd3  The c-pawn is pinned, so the white king must advance up the board.  20.Kxd3  Ra3+  Black soon checkmates. }
19... Rxd1+
{ White resigned here, but let's see how the game could end if Nepomniachtchi wanted to play until checkmate. }
20. Kxd1 Qa1+ 21. Kd2 Qe1# { A precise and spectacular game by Carlsen! } *

